{"title_page": "Yusmadi Yusoff", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{malay name|Yusmadi|Yusoff}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Dewan Negara|Senator]] [[Malay titles|Tuan]]\n| name             = Yusmadi Yusoff\n| native_name      = \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0645\u0627\u062f\u064a \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Mohd Yusmadi bin Mohd Yusoff\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1974|10|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Penang]], [[Malaysia]]\n| residence        = \n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| citizenship      = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| constituency_MP  = [[Balik Pulau (federal constituency)|Balik Pulau]], Penang\n| parliament       = Malaysian\n| term_start       = 2008\n| term_end         = 2013\n| majority         = 708 (2008)\n| predecessor      = Hilmi Yahaya ([[UMNO]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor        = Hilmi Yahaya ([[UMNO]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| office2          = \n| term_start2      = \n| term_end2        = \n| constituency_AM2 = \n| assembly2        = \n| predecessor2     = \n| successor2       = \n| office3          = \n| term_start3      = \n| term_end3        = \n| predecessor3     = \n| successor3       = \n| constituency3    = \n| party            = [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]]\n| otherparty       = [[Pakatan Harapan]]\n| profession       = Lawyer\n| occupation       = Politician\n| relations        = \n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| alma_mater       = [[International Islamic University Malaysia]]<br>\n[[American University Washington College of Law]]\n| website          = {{Unbulleted list\n |{{url|http://rights.com.my/}}\n |{{url|http://www.fny.my/}}\n |{{url|http://yusmadi.my/}}\n}}\n| footnotes        = \n}}\n\n'''Mohd Yusmadi bin Mohd Yusoff''' ([[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0645\u0627\u062f\u064a \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641; born 12 October 1974) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician and was the Member of the [[Parliament of Malaysia]] for the [[Balik Pulau (federal constituency)|Balik Pulau]] constituency in [[Penang]], Malaysia from 2008 to 2013. He sat in [[Parliament]] as a member of [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR).\n\nYusmadi now holds an appointment as a Senator in ''[[Dewan Negara]]''. the Upper House of [[Parliament of Malaysia]] to represent Penang. He was appointed in August 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/08/28/12-pakatan-and-warisan-members-made-senators/|title=12 Pakatan and Warisan members made senators |date=28 August 2018 |work=|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|language=|accessdate=3 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nYusmadi was appointed as the chairman of the Senate Reform Working Committee. The appointment was made unanimous by all senators in the Dewan Negara on 20 December 2018.\n\nThe lawyer-turned-politician is also a political aide to [[Anwar Ibrahim|Dato Seri\u2019 Anwar bin Ibrahim]], a Malaysian politician who is currently the president of the People's Justice Party (''Malay: [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|Parti KeAdilan]]'' [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|''Rakyat)'']].\n\nYusmadi has been appointed as '''Adjunct Professor at ISTAC IIUM (International Institute of Islamic Thought and Civilization)''' with effect from 1 March 2019 on Pro bono basis. Areas of research are Islam, democracy and political ethics.\n\nOn October 2019, Senator Yusmadi was selected by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Singapore as the first '''Lee Kuan Yew Senior Fellow in Public Service''' at '''Lee Kuan School of Public Policy, National University of Singapore.'''\n\nOn December 2019, Senator Yusmadi Yusoff was unanimously elected as the '''first Dewan Negara Caucus Chairman''' during its first meeting today.\n\n==Early Years and Education==\nYusmadi Yusoff was born in [[Balik Pulau]], Penang. Balik Pulau is so dear to his heart that he personally believes the underlying meaning of the acronym \u2018BP\u2019 is \u2018Beyond Possibilities\u2019. He began his education at Sekolah Rendah Kebangsaan Sungai Korok, Balik Pulau. He then continued with his secondary school at SMKA Al Mashoor) (L), Pulau Pinang and ended it at Kolej Islam Alam Shah, Klang.\n\nHe received his Bachelor of Law (Hons.) from [[International Islamic University Malaysia]] (IIUM). In 2007, he completed his Master studies in International Legal Studies (Human Rights) from the [[American University, Washington College of Law|American University Washington College of Law]], [[Washington, D.C.]] Upholding by the quote of knowledge is virtue, he was then selected as Draper Hills Democracy & Development Fellow by Centre of Democracy, Development & the Rule of Law (CDDRL)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cddrl.fsi.stanford.edu/|title=FSI {{!}} CDDRL - Center on Democracy, Development and the Rule of Law|website=cddrl.fsi.stanford.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> at [[Stanford University]], [[California]] in 2008.\n\n== Professional Careers ==\n=== Partner, Fahda Nur & Yusmadi ===\nYusmadi is a legal practitioner by profession. He specializes in public interest litigation and criminal defense cases. He has been involved as a leading counsel and co-counsel in many high-profile civil and criminal cases. Some of the renowned cases that were handled by him involved politicians, top singers and activists namely Al-Maunah case, Dato\u2019 Seri Anwar Ibrahim and Rock Band Search, force eviction cases, Reformasi activists. He is also active in defending cases assigned by YBGK (National Legal Aid Foundation).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hakam.org.my/wp/tag/national-legal-aid-foundation-ybgk/|title=National Legal Aid Foundation (YBGK) {{!}} HAKAM|website=hakam.org.my|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> His pride and joy, Fahda Nur & Yusmadi<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fny.my/|title=Home|work=FNY|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en-US}}</ref> is a boutique law firm which focuses on civil law, commercial, crime, human rights, public interests and Islamic law.\n\n=== RIGHTS Foundation ===\nHis passion towards human rights is undebatable that resulted to the establishment of RIGHTS Foundation.<ref name=\"RIGHTS\">{{Cite web|url=http://rights.my/|title=RIGHTS|website=rights.my|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> He is the founder and chairman of the non-profit organization RIGHTS Foundation which promotes constructive engagement and interaction on the issues of Governance, Human Rights and Social Justice in the region through forums, seminars, advocacy work, dialogues and publications. RIGHTS focal points consist of The Idea of RIGHTS, The Institution of RIGHTS and RIGHTS Hidden Hands.<ref name=\"RIGHTS\"/>\n\n== Public Service Experience ==\n\n=== Parliamentarian ===\nYusmadi was elected as the [[Dewan Rakyat|Member of Parliament]] for Balik Pulau, Penang during the Malaysia General Election in 2008. He broke the record by winning the seat for the first time ever since 1999 for PKR with the majority of 708 votes against Norraesah Binti Mohamad ([[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]]).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php|title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM KE-12|website=semak.spr.gov.my|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> Nevertheless, during the Malaysia General Election in 2013, he was not contested to focus on his non-profit organizations and human rights activities, as well as to make way for [[Muhammad Bakhtiar Wan Chik]], who was eventually unsuccessful in winning the seat<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://resultpru13.spr.gov.my/module/keputusan/paparan/5_KeputusanDR.php?kod=05300|title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM - PARLIMEN|website=resultpru13.spr.gov.my|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+[[Parliament of Malaysia]] : P53 [[Balik Pulau (federal constituency)|Balik Pulau]], [[Penang]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n!Year\n!Opposition\n!Votes\n!Pct\n!Government\n!Votes\n!Pct\n!Ballots cast\n!Majority\n!Turnout\n|-\n|2008\n|'''Yusmadi Yusoff ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])'''\n|15,749\n|50.17%\n|Norraesah Mohamad ([[United Malay National Organization|UMNO]])\n|15,041\n|47.92%\n|31,391\n|708\n|78.94%\n|}\n\nDuring his tenure as the Member of Parliament, he was appointed by [[Yang di-Pertuan Agong|His Majesty the King]] as the Member of the Parliamentary Committee for Anti-Corruption under the umbrella of [[Malaysian Anti-Corruption Commission]] (MACC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sprm.gov.my/index.php/en/|title=Malaysian Anti-Corruption Commission (MACC) - Home|website=www.sprm.gov.my|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> He also became an active spokesperson who championed the issues that were related to education and international affairs. He was appointed to many inter-parliamentarian committees including the Treasurer for [[Inter-Parliamentary Union|Inter-Parliamentary Union (IPU Malaysia)]], Secretary for ASEAN Inter Parliamentary Myanmar Caucus (AIPMC), the Malaysia-European Union Caucus, the Malaysia-South Korea Caucus and Malaysia-Indonesia Caucus.\n\n=== Senate Reform ===\nSenator Yusmadi Yusoff was appointed as the chairman of the Senate Reform Working Committee. The appointment was made unanimous by all senators in the Dewan Negara on 20 December 2018. The former Balik Pulau MP was the senator of the Senate in August. The working committee was set up to improve the institution. the establishment of a discussion between the members of the committee and the consent of the Senate President Tan Sri SA Vigneswaran. Among the matters to be proposed for the Senate reform is to raise the independence of the Senate as provided by the Constitution and to educate the public on the function of the institution. The Senate Reform Working Committee is capable of uniting members of Dewan Negara with different political ideologies to achieve the bigger interest of national development.\n\n=== Akademi Rakyat ===\nAkademi Rakyat<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.facebook.com/Akademi-Rakyat-388678621212225/?_rdc=1&_rdr|title=Akademi Rakyat|website=web.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> was Yusmadi's brainchild that was inspired by the successful of ''Yayasan Anda'' (spearheaded by Dato Seri\u2019 Anwar Ibrahim). Akademi Rakyat was established in 2012 and designed to empower the suburban community in Balik Pulau.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penang.gov.my/en/dmedia/2097-majlis-perasmian-akademi-rakyat-balik-pulau|title=Portal Rasmi Kerajaan Negeri Pulau Pinang - Majlis Perasmian Akademi Rakyat Balik Pulau|website=www.penang.gov.my|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> It was catered to people who did not possess the luxury to seek knowledge as he believes that \"''knowledge is power, information'' ''is liberating, and education is the premise of progress, in every society, in every family\u201d.'' Akademi Rakyat was equipped with the latest educational facilities, reference books and comfortable learning places.\n\n=== Fellow at Institute for Policy Research (known as ''Institut Kajian Dasar'' (IKD)) ===\nHe was elected as the fellow for Institute for Policy Research<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ikd.org.my/|title=- Institut Kajian Dasar|website=ikd.org.my|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> from 2006 until 2008. The Institute for Policy Research was formed by Dato Seri\u2019 Anwar Ibrahim in 1985. This organization was aimed to the cause of cultural revivalism, the construction of a civil society and the promotion of interaction among Southeast Asian countries, between the region and the rest of the world.\n\n== International Involvement ==\nHis forte is not only recognized in [[Malaysia]], but across the globe. He was selected for the [[International Visitor Leadership Program|International Visitors Leadership Program]] (IVLP) for Multi Regional Human Rights Advocacy Programme in the [[United States|United States of America]] in 2004. Not stopping there, in 2006 he was awarded the [[Hubert H. Humphrey Fellowship]] (Law & Human Rights) by the [[Fulbright Commission]] hosted by [[Washington College of Law|American University Washington]] College of Law, Washington D.C due to his active participation in fighting for the course of [[human rights]].\n\nPutting aside his long suit and fervent in human rights, he is also an active member of the international legal community, where he is being invited regularly as a speaker by international governments to forums. Some of the forums were the Doha Forum (Qatar), [[World Forum for Democracy]] (Strasbourg), [[Forum 2000]] (Prague), and Tamil Eelam Human Rights Protection Conference (Chennai). He was also appointed by the Secretary General of Commonwealth to be part of the Commonwealth Election Observation Team<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thecommonwealth.org/elections-observation|title=Elections Observation {{!}} The Commonwealth|last=(http://www.hydrant.co.uk)|first=Site designed and built by Hydrant|website=thecommonwealth.org|language=en|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> for Maldives Presidential Election in 2013. He was one of the [[Election observers|Election Observers]] at [[Virginia]] and [[Maryland]] during the US Mid Term Election in 2007 organized by the Center for Democracy & Election Management,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sourcewatch.org/index.php/Center_for_Democracy_and_Election_Management|title=Center for Democracy and Election Management - SourceWatch|website=www.sourcewatch.org|language=en|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> [[American University]], [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\n== Publication - ''Lelaki Di Sebalik Pulau'' ==\nYusmadi is a prolific writer and his views on law and politics are sought after by both print and electronic media in Malaysia. ''Lelaki Di Sebalik Pulau'' or literally translated as The Man Behind the Island was the testament to verify the statement. The book was written by him and published in 2015. It was a depiction of his view of law and society. The book serves both as a device for the reader to improve their legal understanding and the effect on the real world.\n\n== Film / Documentary ==\nSpecial guest in [[A Whisper to a Roar|A Whisper To A Roar]] in 2009, a collaborative project between [[Stanford University]] and Prince Hecham Maulay Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://moulayhichamfoundation.org/|title=Accueil {{!}} MOULAY HICHAM FOUNDATION|website=moulayhichamfoundation.org|language=en|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> It was directed and produced by [[Ben Moses]] an [[Emmy Award]] winning creator of [[Good Morning, Vietnam|\u2018Good Morning, Vietnam]]\u2019. In 2004, he was the main feature actor in \u2018A Neighbouring Country Story\u2019 on Phoenix Channel, [[Hong Kong]].\n\n== The Concept of ''Muafakat'' (Consensus) ==\nYusmadi is known for his optimistic, objective and positive point of view.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesundaily.my/news/2018/04/07/yusmadi-goes-positive-approach-and-issue-solving|title=Yusmadi goes for positive approach and issue solving|website=www.thesundaily.my|language=en|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> He focuses on people-centric issues to drive him forward. He does not opt for populism or dabbles in hatred form of politics when the actual issue that should be focused on is the people.\n\nHe is a strong believer in the concept of ''Muafakat'' (consensus).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.keadilandaily.com/junjung-muafakat-dalam-pemilihan-keadilan-yusmadi/|title=Junjung muafakat dalam pemilihan KEADILAN \u2013 Yusmadi {{!}} KeadilanDaily.com|website=www.keadilandaily.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> Quoted from The Star pertaining to his view on the upcoming 2018 PKR Election, he said, ''\u201cThe formula for PKR to be stronger is'' ''through Muafakat. To me, M''uafakat ''is not only just about consensus and cooperation but M''uafakat ''is an accord between the concerned stakeholders for a bigger agenda. And the bigger agenda is only one \u2013 for PKR to be the most sustainable, leading party for a new government\u201d''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/opinion/columnists/its-just-politics/2018/08/12/too-close-to-pick-the-battle-between-team-azmin-and-team-rafizi-for-the-pkr-no-2-spot-hots-up-while/|title=Too close to pick  - It's Just Politics {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref>''.''\n\nHe believes that consensus is a form of democracy that portrays maturity with the elements of social value and humanity being infused for the sake of greater interest rather than self-interest.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Malaysian Senators}}\n{{Portal bar|Malaysia|Biography|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yusoff, Yusmadi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:People from Penang]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Malay descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Malaysian lawyers]]<!--Date of admission: 11 June 1999-->\n[[Category:People's Justice Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Negara]]\n[[Category:International Islamic University Malaysia alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{malay name|Yusmadi|Yusoff}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Dewan Negara|Senator]] [[Malay titles|Tuan]]\n| name             = Yusmadi Yusoff\n| native_name      = \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0645\u0627\u062f\u064a \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Mohd Yusmadi bin Mohd Yusoff\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1974|10|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Penang]], [[Malaysia]]\n| residence        = \n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| citizenship      = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| constituency_MP  = [[Balik Pulau (federal constituency)|Balik Pulau]], Penang\n| parliament       = Malaysian\n| term_start       = 2008\n| term_end         = 2013\n| majority         = 708 (2008)\n| predecessor      = Hilmi Yahaya ([[UMNO]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor        = Hilmi Yahaya ([[UMNO]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| office2          = \n| term_start2      = \n| term_end2        = \n| constituency_AM2 = \n| assembly2        = \n| predecessor2     = \n| successor2       = \n| office3          = \n| term_start3      = \n| term_end3        = \n| predecessor3     = \n| successor3       = \n| constituency3    = \n| party            = [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]]\n| otherparty       = [[Pakatan Harapan]]\n| profession       = Lawyer\n| occupation       = Politician\n| relations        = \n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| alma_mater       = [[International Islamic University Malaysia]]<br>\n[[American University Washington College of Law]]\n| website          = {{Unbulleted list\n |{{url|http://rights.com.my/}}\n |{{url|http://www.fny.my/}}\n |{{url|http://yusmadi.my/}}\n}}\n| footnotes        = \n}}\n\n'''Mohd Yusmadi bin Mohd Yusoff''' ([[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0645\u0627\u062f\u064a \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641; born 12 October 1974) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician and was the Member of the [[Parliament of Malaysia]] for the [[Balik Pulau (federal constituency)|Balik Pulau]] constituency in [[Penang]], Malaysia from 2008 to 2013. He sat in [[Parliament]] as a member of [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR).\n\nYusmadi now holds an appointment as a Senator in ''[[Dewan Negara]]''. the Upper House of [[Parliament of Malaysia]] to represent Penang. He was appointed in August 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/08/28/12-pakatan-and-warisan-members-made-senators/|title=12 Pakatan and Warisan members made senators |date=28 August 2018 |work=|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|language=|accessdate=3 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nYusmadi was appointed as the chairman of the Senate Reform Working Committee. The appointment was made unanimous by all senators in the Dewan Negara on 20 December 2018.\n\nThe lawyer-turned-politician is also a political aide to [[Anwar Ibrahim|Dato Seri\u2019 Anwar bin Ibrahim]], a Malaysian politician who is currently the president of the People's Justice Party (''Malay: [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|Parti KeAdilan]]'' [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|''Rakyat)'']].\n\nYusmadi has been appointed as '''Adjunct Professor at ISTAC IIUM (International Institute of Islamic Thought and Civilization)''' with effect from 1 March 2019 on Pro bono basis. Areas of research are Islam, democracy and political ethics.\n\nOn October 2019, Senator Yusmadi was selected by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Singapore as the first '''Lee Kuan Yew Senior Fellow in Public Service''' at '''Lee Kuan School of Public Policy, National University of Singapore.''' \n\nOn December 2019, Senator Yusmadi Yusoff was unanimously elected as the '''first Dewan Negara Caucus Chairman''' during its first meeting today.\n\n==Early Years and Education==\nYusmadi Yusoff was born in [[Balik Pulau]], Penang. Balik Pulau is so dear to his heart that he personally believes the underlying meaning of the acronym \u2018BP\u2019 is \u2018Beyond Possibilities\u2019. He began his education at Sekolah Rendah Kebangsaan Sungai Korok, Balik Pulau. He then continued with his secondary school at SMKA Al Mashoor) (L), Pulau Pinang and ended it at Kolej Islam Alam Shah, Klang.\n\nHe received his Bachelor of Law (Hons.) from [[International Islamic University Malaysia]] (IIUM). In 2007, he completed his Master studies in International Legal Studies (Human Rights) from the [[American University, Washington College of Law|American University Washington College of Law]], [[Washington, D.C.]] Upholding by the quote of knowledge is virtue, he was then selected as Draper Hills Democracy & Development Fellow by Centre of Democracy, Development & the Rule of Law (CDDRL)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cddrl.fsi.stanford.edu/|title=FSI {{!}} CDDRL - Center on Democracy, Development and the Rule of Law|website=cddrl.fsi.stanford.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> at [[Stanford University]], [[California]] in 2008.\n\n== Professional Careers ==\n=== Partner, Fahda Nur & Yusmadi ===\nYusmadi is a legal practitioner by profession. He specializes in public interest litigation and criminal defense cases. He has been involved as a leading counsel and co-counsel in many high-profile civil and criminal cases. Some of the renowned cases that were handled by him involved politicians, top singers and activists namely Al-Maunah case, Dato\u2019 Seri Anwar Ibrahim and Rock Band Search, force eviction cases, Reformasi activists. He is also active in defending cases assigned by YBGK (National Legal Aid Foundation).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hakam.org.my/wp/tag/national-legal-aid-foundation-ybgk/|title=National Legal Aid Foundation (YBGK) {{!}} HAKAM|website=hakam.org.my|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> His pride and joy, Fahda Nur & Yusmadi<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fny.my/|title=Home|work=FNY|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en-US}}</ref> is a boutique law firm which focuses on civil law, commercial, crime, human rights, public interests and Islamic law.\n\n=== RIGHTS Foundation ===\nHis passion towards human rights is undebatable that resulted to the establishment of RIGHTS Foundation.<ref name=\"RIGHTS\">{{Cite web|url=http://rights.my/|title=RIGHTS|website=rights.my|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> He is the founder and chairman of the non-profit organization RIGHTS Foundation which promotes constructive engagement and interaction on the issues of Governance, Human Rights and Social Justice in the region through forums, seminars, advocacy work, dialogues and publications. RIGHTS focal points consist of The Idea of RIGHTS, The Institution of RIGHTS and RIGHTS Hidden Hands.<ref name=\"RIGHTS\"/>\n\n== Public Service Experience ==\n\n=== Parliamentarian ===\nYusmadi was elected as the [[Dewan Rakyat|Member of Parliament]] for Balik Pulau, Penang during the Malaysia General Election in 2008. He broke the record by winning the seat for the first time ever since 1999 for PKR with the majority of 708 votes against Norraesah Binti Mohamad ([[United Malays National Organisation|UMNO]]).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php|title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM KE-12|website=semak.spr.gov.my|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> Nevertheless, during the Malaysia General Election in 2013, he was not contested to focus on his non-profit organizations and human rights activities, as well as to make way for [[Muhammad Bakhtiar Wan Chik]], who was eventually unsuccessful in winning the seat<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://resultpru13.spr.gov.my/module/keputusan/paparan/5_KeputusanDR.php?kod=05300|title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM - PARLIMEN|website=resultpru13.spr.gov.my|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+[[Parliament of Malaysia]] : P53 [[Balik Pulau (federal constituency)|Balik Pulau]], [[Penang]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n!Year\n!Opposition\n!Votes\n!Pct\n!Government\n!Votes\n!Pct\n!Ballots cast\n!Majority\n!Turnout\n|-\n|2008\n|'''Yusmadi Yusoff ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])'''\n|15,749\n|50.17%\n|Norraesah Mohamad ([[United Malay National Organization|UMNO]])\n|15,041\n|47.92%\n|31,391\n|708\n|78.94%\n|}\n\nDuring his tenure as the Member of Parliament, he was appointed by [[Yang di-Pertuan Agong|His Majesty the King]] as the Member of the Parliamentary Committee for Anti-Corruption under the umbrella of [[Malaysian Anti-Corruption Commission]] (MACC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sprm.gov.my/index.php/en/|title=Malaysian Anti-Corruption Commission (MACC) - Home|website=www.sprm.gov.my|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> He also became an active spokesperson who championed the issues that were related to education and international affairs. He was appointed to many inter-parliamentarian committees including the Treasurer for [[Inter-Parliamentary Union|Inter-Parliamentary Union (IPU Malaysia)]], Secretary for ASEAN Inter Parliamentary Myanmar Caucus (AIPMC), the Malaysia-European Union Caucus, the Malaysia-South Korea Caucus and Malaysia-Indonesia Caucus.\n\n=== Senate Reform ===\nSenator Yusmadi Yusoff was appointed as the chairman of the Senate Reform Working Committee. The appointment was made unanimous by all senators in the Dewan Negara on 20 December 2018. The former Balik Pulau MP was the senator of the Senate in August. The working committee was set up to improve the institution. the establishment of a discussion between the members of the committee and the consent of the Senate President Tan Sri SA Vigneswaran. Among the matters to be proposed for the Senate reform is to raise the independence of the Senate as provided by the Constitution and to educate the public on the function of the institution. The Senate Reform Working Committee is capable of uniting members of Dewan Negara with different political ideologies to achieve the bigger interest of national development.\n\n=== Akademi Rakyat ===\nAkademi Rakyat<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.facebook.com/Akademi-Rakyat-388678621212225/?_rdc=1&_rdr|title=Akademi Rakyat|website=web.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> was Yusmadi's brainchild that was inspired by the successful of ''Yayasan Anda'' (spearheaded by Dato Seri\u2019 Anwar Ibrahim). Akademi Rakyat was established in 2012 and designed to empower the suburban community in Balik Pulau.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penang.gov.my/en/dmedia/2097-majlis-perasmian-akademi-rakyat-balik-pulau|title=Portal Rasmi Kerajaan Negeri Pulau Pinang - Majlis Perasmian Akademi Rakyat Balik Pulau|website=www.penang.gov.my|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> It was catered to people who did not possess the luxury to seek knowledge as he believes that \"''knowledge is power, information'' ''is liberating, and education is the premise of progress, in every society, in every family\u201d.'' Akademi Rakyat was equipped with the latest educational facilities, reference books and comfortable learning places.\n\n=== Fellow at Institute for Policy Research (known as ''Institut Kajian Dasar'' (IKD)) ===\nHe was elected as the fellow for Institute for Policy Research<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ikd.org.my/|title=- Institut Kajian Dasar|website=ikd.org.my|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> from 2006 until 2008. The Institute for Policy Research was formed by Dato Seri\u2019 Anwar Ibrahim in 1985. This organization was aimed to the cause of cultural revivalism, the construction of a civil society and the promotion of interaction among Southeast Asian countries, between the region and the rest of the world.\n\n== International Involvement ==\nHis forte is not only recognized in [[Malaysia]], but across the globe. He was selected for the [[International Visitor Leadership Program|International Visitors Leadership Program]] (IVLP) for Multi Regional Human Rights Advocacy Programme in the [[United States|United States of America]] in 2004. Not stopping there, in 2006 he was awarded the [[Hubert H. Humphrey Fellowship]] (Law & Human Rights) by the [[Fulbright Commission]] hosted by [[Washington College of Law|American University Washington]] College of Law, Washington D.C due to his active participation in fighting for the course of [[human rights]].\n\nPutting aside his long suit and fervent in human rights, he is also an active member of the international legal community, where he is being invited regularly as a speaker by international governments to forums. Some of the forums were the Doha Forum (Qatar), [[World Forum for Democracy]] (Strasbourg), [[Forum 2000]] (Prague), and Tamil Eelam Human Rights Protection Conference (Chennai). He was also appointed by the Secretary General of Commonwealth to be part of the Commonwealth Election Observation Team<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thecommonwealth.org/elections-observation|title=Elections Observation {{!}} The Commonwealth|last=(http://www.hydrant.co.uk)|first=Site designed and built by Hydrant|website=thecommonwealth.org|language=en|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> for Maldives Presidential Election in 2013. He was one of the [[Election observers|Election Observers]] at [[Virginia]] and [[Maryland]] during the US Mid Term Election in 2007 organized by the Center for Democracy & Election Management,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sourcewatch.org/index.php/Center_for_Democracy_and_Election_Management|title=Center for Democracy and Election Management - SourceWatch|website=www.sourcewatch.org|language=en|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> [[American University]], [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\n== Publication - ''Lelaki Di Sebalik Pulau'' ==\nYusmadi is a prolific writer and his views on law and politics are sought after by both print and electronic media in Malaysia. ''Lelaki Di Sebalik Pulau'' or literally translated as The Man Behind the Island was the testament to verify the statement. The book was written by him and published in 2015. It was a depiction of his view of law and society. The book serves both as a device for the reader to improve their legal understanding and the effect on the real world.\n\n== Film / Documentary ==\nSpecial guest in [[A Whisper to a Roar|A Whisper To A Roar]] in 2009, a collaborative project between [[Stanford University]] and Prince Hecham Maulay Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://moulayhichamfoundation.org/|title=Accueil {{!}} MOULAY HICHAM FOUNDATION|website=moulayhichamfoundation.org|language=en|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> It was directed and produced by [[Ben Moses]] an [[Emmy Award]] winning creator of [[Good Morning, Vietnam|\u2018Good Morning, Vietnam]]\u2019. In 2004, he was the main feature actor in \u2018A Neighbouring Country Story\u2019 on Phoenix Channel, [[Hong Kong]].\n\n== The Concept of ''Muafakat'' (Consensus) ==\nYusmadi is known for his optimistic, objective and positive point of view.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesundaily.my/news/2018/04/07/yusmadi-goes-positive-approach-and-issue-solving|title=Yusmadi goes for positive approach and issue solving|website=www.thesundaily.my|language=en|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> He focuses on people-centric issues to drive him forward. He does not opt for populism or dabbles in hatred form of politics when the actual issue that should be focused on is the people.\n\nHe is a strong believer in the concept of ''Muafakat'' (consensus).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.keadilandaily.com/junjung-muafakat-dalam-pemilihan-keadilan-yusmadi/|title=Junjung muafakat dalam pemilihan KEADILAN \u2013 Yusmadi {{!}} KeadilanDaily.com|website=www.keadilandaily.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> Quoted from The Star pertaining to his view on the upcoming 2018 PKR Election, he said, ''\u201cThe formula for PKR to be stronger is'' ''through Muafakat. To me, M''uafakat ''is not only just about consensus and cooperation but M''uafakat ''is an accord between the concerned stakeholders for a bigger agenda. And the bigger agenda is only one \u2013 for PKR to be the most sustainable, leading party for a new government\u201d''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/opinion/columnists/its-just-politics/2018/08/12/too-close-to-pick-the-battle-between-team-azmin-and-team-rafizi-for-the-pkr-no-2-spot-hots-up-while/|title=Too close to pick  - It's Just Politics {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref>''.''\n\nHe believes that consensus is a form of democracy that portrays maturity with the elements of social value and humanity being infused for the sake of greater interest rather than self-interest.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Malaysian Senators}}\n{{Portal bar|Malaysia|Biography|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yusoff, Yusmadi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:People from Penang]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Malay descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Malaysian lawyers]]<!--Date of admission: 11 June 1999-->\n[[Category:People's Justice Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Negara]]\n[[Category:International Islamic University Malaysia alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian people]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "duplicate categorization; already in subcat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yusmadi_Yusoff"}
{"title_page": "Rosey Yunus", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other salutations|Puan]]\n| name = Rosey Yunus\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of the Star of Hornbill Sarawak#Johan Bintang Kenyalang (J.B.K.)|JBK]] [[Civil Administration Medal (Sarawak)|PPB]] [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| office = Assistant Minister for Women, Family and Childhood Development (Sarawak)\n| governor = [[Abang Muhammad Salahuddin]]<br />[[Abdul Taib Mahmud]]\n| minister = [[Fatimah Abdullah (politician)|Fatimah Abdullah]]\n| 1blankname = Chief Minister\n| 1namedata = Abdul Taib Mahmud<br />[[Adenan Satem]]<br />[[Abang Abdul Rahman Zohari Abang Openg]]\n| predecessor = ''Inaugural holder''\n| term_start = 28 September 2011\n| term_end = \n| successor = \n| constituency = [[Bekenu (state constituency)|Bekenu]]\n| office1 = Chairperson of Miri Port Authority\n| deputy1 = \n| predecessor1 = \n| successor1 = Palu @ Paulus Gumbang\n| term_start1 = 2008\n| term_end1 = 2011\n| assembly2 = Sarawak State Legislative\n| constituency_AM2 = [[Bekenu (state constituency)|Bekenu]]\n| term_start2 = 20 May 2006\n| term_end2 =\n| predecessor2 = ''Constituency established''\n| successor2 = \n| majority2 = 3,072 ([[2006 Sarawak state election|2006]])<br />3,714 ([[2011 Sarawak state election|2011]])<br />4,789 ([[2016 Sarawak state election|2016]])\n| citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| party = [[Progressive Democratic Party (Malaysia)|Sarawak Progressive Democratic Party]] (SDPD)<br />[[Parti Pesaka Bumiputera Bersatu|United Bumiputera Heritage Party]] (PBB)\n| otherparty = [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN)<br />[[Sarawak Parties Alliance]] (GPS)\n| occupation = Politician\n| alma_mater = [[University of Malaya]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1956|01|16}}\n| birth_place = \n| residence = [[Bekenu]], [[Sibuti]], [[Miri]], Sarawak, Malaysia\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| profession = Teacher\n| relations = \n| spouse =\n| children = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Rosey binti Haji Yunus''' (born 16 January 1956)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dunsarawak.blogspot.com/2009/03/kawasan-pilihanraya-n_9047.html|publisher=[[Sarawak State Legislative Assembly]]|year=2008|title=DEWAN UNDANGAN NEGERI SARAWAK|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician from the [[Parti Pesaka Bumiputera Bersatu|United Bumiputera Heritage Party]] (PBB) currently serving as the Assistant Minister for Women, Family and Childhood Development in the [[Cabinet of Sarawak]] and Sarawak state assemblywoman representing [[Bekenu (state constituency)|Bekenu]] constituency.\n\n==Education==\nRosey graduated from the [[University of Malaya]] with a Bachelor of Arts (BA) (Hons) majoring in linguistic art with [[British undergraduate degree classification#Upper second-class honours|upper second-class honours]] and a [[Diploma of Education]] in 1980.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Political career==\nRosey was first elected assemblywoman for Bekenu in the [[2006 Sarawak state election]]. In 2011, she successfully defended her seat in the following elections with an increased majority and was appointed as Assistant Minister for the newly-created Ministry of Welfare, Women & Family Development.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=22 February 2019|url=https://rimauataskerusi.wordpress.com/2011/09/28/the-sarawak-cabinet-2011/|date=28 September 2011|title=The Sarawak Cabinet (2011)|publisher=rimau atas kerusi}}</ref>\n\nRosey was formerly a member of the [[Progressive Democratic Party (Malaysia)|Sarawak Progressive Democratic Party]] (SDPD) before joining then-president [[William Mawan Ikom]] and three other assemblymen in leaving the party in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Astro Awani]]|date=15 May 2014|accessdate=22 February 2019|language=Malay|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/sarawak-sembilan-adun-dua-ahli-parlimen-tinggalkan-parti-35893|title=Sarawak: Sembilan ADUN, dua ahli Parlimen tinggalkan parti}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:90%\"\n|+ '''[[Sarawak State Legislative Assembly]]'''\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Valid ballots\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|'''[[2006 Sarawak state election|2006]]'''\n|rowspan=\"7\"|'''[[Bekenu (state constituency)|Bekenu]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Rosey Yunus'''}} ([[Progressive Democratic Party (Malaysia)|SDPD]] / [[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|4,357\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|77.22\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n||Mohdak Ismail ([[Independent politician|PKR]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|1,285\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|22.78\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|5,642\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|3,072\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|5,757\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|'''[[2011 Sarawak state election|2011]]'''\n|rowspan=\"3\" {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|rowspan=\"3\"|{{nowrap|'''Rosey Yunus'''}} ([[Progressive Democratic Party (Malaysia)|SDPD]] / [[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\"|4,946\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\"|70.34\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n||Ishak Mahwi ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|1,232\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|17.52\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\" |7,032\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\" |3,714\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\" |7,135\n|-\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n||Thony Badak ([[Sarawak National Party|SNAP]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|570\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|8.10\n|-\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Independent}} |\n||Dyg Juliana Awg Tambi ([[Love Malaysia Party|PCM]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|284\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|4.04\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" |'''[[2016 Sarawak state election|2016]]'''\n|rowspan=\"3\" {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|rowspan=\"3\" |{{nowrap|'''Rosey Yunus'''}} ([[Parti Pesaka Bumiputera Bersatu|PBB]] / [[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n|rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:right;\"|6,009\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\" |71.68\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n||Bill Kayong ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|1,220\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|14.45\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\" |8,383\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\" |4,789\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\" |8,540\n|-\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Independent}} |\n||Austin Sigi Melu ([[Independent politician|IND]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|589\n||7.03\n|-\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Independent}} |\n||Joe @ Peter Jelin ([[Independent politician|IND]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|565\n||6.74\n|-\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n* {{Flag|Sarawak}} :\n** [[File:MY-SAR Medal of Public Administration - Pingat Pentadbiran Awam.svg|50px]] Meritorious Service Medal-Silver [[Civil Administration Medal (Sarawak)]] (PPB)<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://bekenusibuti2.gbs2u.com/bd/index3.asp?userid=75845106&idno=2|accessdate=22 February 2019|title=LAMAN WEB PERKHIDMATAN|publisher=PEJABAT PUSAT KHIDMAT WAKIL RAKYAT BARISAN NASIONAL N.71 BEKENU|year=2015}}</ref>\n** [[File:MY-SAR Order of the Star of the Hornbill (Bintang Kenyalang) - 4 Companion (JBK).svg|50px]] Companion of the [[Order of the Star of Hornbill Sarawak#Johan Bintang Kenyalang (J.B.K.)|Order of the Star of Hornbill Sarawak]] (JBK) (2010)<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web|date=19 October 2010|accessdate=22 February 2019|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/story/?file=/2010/10/19/sarawak/7245629&sec=|title=Sarawak Yang DiPertua Negeri's Birthday Honours list 2010|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bekenu (state constituency)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yunus, Rosey}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:University of Malaya alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n[[Category:Parti Pesaka Bumiputera Bersatu politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Sarawak State Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Star of Hornbill Sarawak]]\n[[Category:Women MLAs in Sarawak]]\n[[Category:People from Sarawak]]\n[[Category:Sarawak Progressive Democratic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Malay descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women in Sarawak politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other salutations|Puan]]\n| name = Rosey Yunus\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of the Star of Hornbill Sarawak#Johan Bintang Kenyalang (J.B.K.)|JBK]] [[Civil Administration Medal (Sarawak)|PPB]] [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| office = Assistant Minister for Women, Family and Childhood Development (Sarawak)\n| governor = [[Abang Muhammad Salahuddin]]<br />[[Abdul Taib Mahmud]]\n| minister = [[Fatimah Abdullah (politician)|Fatimah Abdullah]]\n| 1blankname = Chief Minister\n| 1namedata = Abdul Taib Mahmud<br />[[Adenan Satem]]<br />[[Abang Abdul Rahman Zohari Abang Openg]]\n| predecessor = ''Inaugural holder''\n| term_start = 28 September 2011\n| term_end = \n| successor = \n| constituency = [[Bekenu (state constituency)|Bekenu]]\n| office1 = Chairperson of Miri Port Authority\n| deputy1 = \n| predecessor1 = \n| successor1 = Palu @ Paulus Gumbang\n| term_start1 = 2008\n| term_end1 = 2011\n| assembly2 = Sarawak State Legislative\n| constituency_AM2 = [[Bekenu (state constituency)|Bekenu]]\n| term_start2 = 20 May 2006\n| term_end2 =\n| predecessor2 = ''Constituency established''\n| successor2 = \n| majority2 = 3,072 ([[2006 Sarawak state election|2006]])<br />3,714 ([[2011 Sarawak state election|2011]])<br />4,789 ([[2016 Sarawak state election|2016]])\n| citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| party = [[Progressive Democratic Party (Malaysia)|Sarawak Progressive Democratic Party]] (SDPD)<br />[[Parti Pesaka Bumiputera Bersatu|United Bumiputera Heritage Party]] (PBB)\n| otherparty = [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN)<br />[[Sarawak Parties Alliance]] (GPS)\n| occupation = Politician\n| alma_mater = [[University of Malaya]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1956|01|16}}\n| birth_place = \n| residence = [[Bekenu]], [[Sibuti]], [[Miri]], Sarawak, Malaysia\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| profession = Teacher\n| relations = \n| spouse =\n| children = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Rosey binti Haji Yunus''' (born 16 January 1956)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dunsarawak.blogspot.com/2009/03/kawasan-pilihanraya-n_9047.html|publisher=[[Sarawak State Legislative Assembly]]|year=2008|title=DEWAN UNDANGAN NEGERI SARAWAK|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician from the [[Parti Pesaka Bumiputera Bersatu|United Bumiputera Heritage Party]] (PBB) currently serving as the Assistant Minister for Women, Family and Childhood Development in the [[Cabinet of Sarawak]] and Sarawak state assemblywoman representing [[Bekenu (state constituency)|Bekenu]] constituency.\n\n==Education==\nRosey graduated from the [[University of Malaya]] with a Bachelor of Arts (BA) (Hons) majoring in linguistic art with [[British undergraduate degree classification#Upper second-class honours|upper second-class honours]] and a [[Diploma of Education]] in 1980.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Political career==\nRosey was first elected assemblywoman for Bekenu in the [[2006 Sarawak state election]]. In 2011, she successfully defended her seat in the following elections with an increased majority and was appointed as Assistant Minister for the newly-created Ministry of Welfare, Women & Family Development.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=22 February 2019|url=https://rimauataskerusi.wordpress.com/2011/09/28/the-sarawak-cabinet-2011/|date=28 September 2011|title=The Sarawak Cabinet (2011)|publisher=rimau atas kerusi}}</ref>\n\nRosey was formerly a member of the [[Progressive Democratic Party (Malaysia)|Sarawak Progressive Democratic Party]] (SDPD) before joining then-president [[William Mawan Ikom]] and three other assemblymen in leaving the party in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Astro Awani]]|date=15 May 2014|accessdate=22 February 2019|language=Malay|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/sarawak-sembilan-adun-dua-ahli-parlimen-tinggalkan-parti-35893|title=Sarawak: Sembilan ADUN, dua ahli Parlimen tinggalkan parti}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:90%\"\n|+ '''[[Sarawak State Legislative Assembly]]'''\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Valid ballots\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|'''[[2006 Sarawak state election|2006]]'''\n|rowspan=\"7\"|'''[[Bekenu (state constituency)|Bekenu]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Rosey Yunus'''}} ([[Progressive Democratic Party (Malaysia)|SDPD]] / [[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|4,357\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|77.22\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n||Mohdak Ismail ([[Independent politician|PKR]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|1,285\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|22.78\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|5,642\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|3,072\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|5,757\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|'''[[2011 Sarawak state election|2011]]'''\n|rowspan=\"3\" {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|rowspan=\"3\"|{{nowrap|'''Rosey Yunus'''}} ([[Progressive Democratic Party (Malaysia)|SDPD]] / [[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\"|4,946\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\"|70.34\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n||Ishak Mahwi ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|1,232\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|17.52\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\" |7,032\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\" |3,714\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\" |7,135\n|-\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n||Thony Badak ([[Sarawak National Party|SNAP]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|570\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|8.10\n|-\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Independent}} |\n||Dyg Juliana Awg Tambi ([[Love Malaysia Party|PCM]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|284\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|4.04\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" |'''[[2016 Sarawak state election|2016]]'''\n|rowspan=\"3\" {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|rowspan=\"3\" |{{nowrap|'''Rosey Yunus'''}} ([[Parti Pesaka Bumiputera Bersatu|PBB]] / [[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n|rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:right;\"|6,009\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\" |71.68\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n||Bill Kayong ([[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|PKR]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|1,220\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|14.45\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\" |8,383\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\" |4,789\n|style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"3\" |8,540\n|-\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Independent}} |\n||Austin Sigi Melu ([[Independent politician|IND]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|589\n||7.03\n|-\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Independent}} |\n||Joe @ Peter Jelin ([[Independent politician|IND]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|565\n||6.74\n|-\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n* {{Flag|Sarawak}} :\n** [[File:MY-SAR Medal of Public Administration - Pingat Pentadbiran Awam.svg|50px]] Meritorious Service Medal-Silver [[Civil Administration Medal (Sarawak)]] (PPB)<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://bekenusibuti2.gbs2u.com/bd/index3.asp?userid=75845106&idno=2|accessdate=22 February 2019|title=LAMAN WEB PERKHIDMATAN|publisher=PEJABAT PUSAT KHIDMAT WAKIL RAKYAT BARISAN NASIONAL N.71 BEKENU|year=2015}}</ref>\n** [[File:MY-SAR Order of the Star of the Hornbill (Bintang Kenyalang) - 4 Companion (JBK).svg|50px]] Companion of the [[Order of the Star of Hornbill Sarawak#Johan Bintang Kenyalang (J.B.K.)|Order of the Star of Hornbill Sarawak]] (JBK) (2010)<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web|date=19 October 2010|accessdate=22 February 2019|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/story/?file=/2010/10/19/sarawak/7245629&sec=|title=Sarawak Yang DiPertua Negeri's Birthday Honours list 2010|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bekenu (state constituency)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yunus, Rosey}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:University of Malaya alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian people]]\n[[Category:Parti Pesaka Bumiputera Bersatu politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Sarawak State Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Star of Hornbill Sarawak]]\n[[Category:Women MLAs in Sarawak]]\n[[Category:People from Sarawak]]\n[[Category:Sarawak Progressive Democratic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Malay descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women in Sarawak politics]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:duplicate categorization; already in subcat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rosey_Yunus"}
{"title_page": "Violet Yong", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other titles|Puan]]\n| name = Violet Yong Wui Wui\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n| native_name = {{nobold|\u6768\u8587\u8bb3}}\n| native_name_lang = zh-my\n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| caption = Violet Yong, DAP politician from Malaysia\n| assembly = Sarawak State Legislative\n| constituency_AM = [[Pending (state constituency)|Pending]]\n| term_start = 20 May 2006\n| term_end =\n| predecessor = [[Sim Kheng Hui]] ([[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor = \n| majority = 4,372 ([[2006 Sarawak state election|2006]])<br />7,595 ([[2011 Sarawak state election|2011]])<br />5,012 ([[2016 Sarawak state election|2016]])\n| citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| party = [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP)\n| otherparty = [[Pakatan Rakyat]] (PR)<br />[[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH)\n| occupation = [[Politician]], [[Lawyer]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Melbourne]], [[Australia]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|4|04|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| relations =\n| spouse =\n| children = \n| website = {{url|http://violetyong.blogspot.com/}} <br /> {{url|https://www.facebook.com/violet.yong.1}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Violet Yong Wui Wui''' ({{zh|s=\u6768\u8587\u8bb3|t=\u694a\u8587\u8af1|p=Y\u00e1ng W\u0113ihu\u00ec}}) is a [[Malaysians|Malaysian]] [[lawyer]] and [[politician]] from the [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) currently serving as the [[Deliberative assembly|assemblywoman]] of the [[Sarawak State Assembly]] for [[Pending (state constituency)|Pending]] constituency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ictu.tmp.sarawak.gov.my/seg.php?recordID=M0055&contentID=SM0112 |title=Sarawak Government Official Portal |website=Ictu.tmp.sarawak.gov.my |date= |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dunsarawak.blogspot.my/2009/03/kawasan-pilihanraya-n_4294.html |title=Dewan Undangan Negeri Sarawak |website=Dunsarawak.blogspot.my |date=2004-02-26 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref> She won the seat of N10 Pending for three consecutive terms, in the Sarawak state elections of 2006, 2011 and 2016.\n\n==Education==\nYong is a holder of [[Bachelor of Laws]] from [[University of Melbourne]], [[Australia]].<ref name=\"biodata\">{{cite web|url=http://library.perdana.org.my/Digital_Content/Serials/EDGE/2006-JAN/Eastern%20promise%20%5B41%5D.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 7, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531231450/http://library.perdana.org.my/Digital_Content/Serials/EDGE/2006-JAN/Eastern%20promise%20%5B41%5D.pdf |archivedate=May 31, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nYong is a practicing lawyer at Chong Brothers Advocates, [[Kuching]] which is owned by [[Ministry of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs]], DAP [[Sarawak]] Chairperson and [[Stampin (federal constituency)|Stampin]] [[Member of Parliament]] (MP), [[Chong Chieng Jen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sarawak-advocates.org.my/index.php/rolls-a-directories/legal-firms/86-chong-brothers-advocates |title=Chong Brothers Advocates. (Kuching) |website=Sarawak-advocates.org.my |date=2016-04-06 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nYong's initiation to [[politics]] began as a child. As a first-hand witness to politics, she tagged along with her parents, active [[Democratic Action Party|DAP]] members, to party activities and while they helped with canvassing during state elections.<ref name=\"biodata\"/>\n\nYong joined the [[Democratic Action Party]] at the age of 29 after graduating from [[Melbourne]]. In early 2005, some party leaders in the state lobbied for her to be a candidate.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2011/01/31/woman-of-substance/ |title=Woman of substance - Community &#124; The Star Online |website=Thestar.com.my |date=2011-01-31 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\nHer big win came in the [[2006 Sarawak state election]] when she won the seat of [[Pending (state constituency)]], which was considered to be an [[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]] stronghold since 1991. From then on, she has continued to gain substantial majority in the ensuing state elections for her constituency.\n\nWithin her political party, she also heads the Women's Affairs department.<ref name=\"biodata\"/>\n\nYong is sometimes associated with the [[moniker]] \"Cili Padi\" or [[Bird's eye chilli]] in English due to her pluckiness at voicing out problems and issues affecting the people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2fVxc6NCumA |title=DAP Ceramah by YB Violet Yong a.k.a. Cili Padi part 1 |publisher=YouTube |date=2013-05-02 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n===Sarawak State Election, 2006===\nYong pulled off one of the biggest upsets in the [[2006 Sarawak state election]] when she defeated [[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]] secretary general [[Malay titles#Datuk|Datuk]] [[Sim Kheng Hui]] with a majority of 4,372 votes.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/09/21/dr-sim-weve-three-names-for-pending/ |title=Dr Sim: We\u2019ve three names for Pending \u2013 BorneoPost Online &#124; Borneo , Malaysia, Sarawak Daily News &#124; Largest English Daily In Borneo |website=Theborneopost.com |date=2015-09-21 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/print/malaysia/former-classmates-to-lock-horns-in-pending |title=Former classmates to lock horns in Pending &#124; Malaysia |publisher=Malay Mail Online |date=2016-05-04 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref> Before he was defeated in 2006, Datuk Sim had been assemblyman of [[Pending (state constituency)]] since 1991.\n\n===Sarawak State Election, 2011===\nIn the [[2011 Sarawak state election]], Yong received 14,375 votes and won with a majority of 7,595 votes. She defeated Dr. [[Sim Kui Hian]] from [[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]] under [[Barisan Nasional]] who received 6,780 votes.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2011/03/07/dr-sim-to-resign-from-health-dept-soon/ |title=Dr Sim to resign from Health Dept soon - Community &#124; The Star Online |website=Thestar.com.my |date=2011-03-07 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n===Sarawak State Election, 2016===\nIn the [[2016 Sarawak state election]], Violet Yong won the seat of N10 [[Pending (state constituency)]] for a third term against incoming [[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]] candidate [[Milton Foo Tiang Wee]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsarawaktribune.com/news/56084/3-corner-fight-in-Padungan-and-Batu-Lintang-straight-fight-in-Pending/ |title=3-corner fight in Padungan and Batu Lintang, straight fight in Pending |newspaper=[[New Sarawak Tribune]] |date= |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:90%\"\n|+ '''[[Sarawak State Legislative Assembly]]'''\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Government\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Valid ballots\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n||'''[[2006 Sarawak state election|2006]]'''\n|rowspan=\"3\"|'''[[Pending (state constituency)|Pending]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Violet Yong Wui Wui'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|11,632\n|61.57\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n||Sim Kheng Hui ([[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]] / [[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|7,260\n||38.43\n||18,892\n||4,372\n||19,203\n|-\n||'''[[2011 Sarawak state election|2011]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Violet Yong Wui Wui'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|14,375\n|67.95\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n||Dr. [[Sim Kui Hian]] ([[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]] / [[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|6,780\n||32.05\n||21,155\n||7,595\n||21,310\n|-\n||'''[[2016 Sarawak state election|2016]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Violet Yong Wui Wui'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|12,454\n|62.60\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n||[[Milton Foo Tiang Wee]] ([[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]] / [[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|7,442\n||37.40\n||19,896\n||5,012\n||20,038\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pending (state constituency)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yong, Violet}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n[[Category:Sarawak politicians]]\n[[Category:Malaysian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Democratic Action Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Sarawak State Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Women MLAs in Sarawak]]\n[[Category:University of Melbourne alumni]]\n[[Category:Malaysian politicians of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Women in Sarawak politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other titles|Puan]]\n| name = Violet Yong Wui Wui\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n| native_name = {{nobold|\u6768\u8587\u8bb3}}\n| native_name_lang = zh-my\n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| caption = Violet Yong, DAP politician from Malaysia\n| assembly = Sarawak State Legislative\n| constituency_AM = [[Pending (state constituency)|Pending]]\n| term_start = 20 May 2006\n| term_end =\n| predecessor = [[Sim Kheng Hui]] ([[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor = \n| majority = 4,372 ([[2006 Sarawak state election|2006]])<br />7,595 ([[2011 Sarawak state election|2011]])<br />5,012 ([[2016 Sarawak state election|2016]])\n| citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| party = [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP)\n| otherparty = [[Pakatan Rakyat]] (PR)<br />[[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH)\n| occupation = [[Politician]], [[Lawyer]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Melbourne]], [[Australia]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|4|04|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| relations =\n| spouse =\n| children = \n| website = {{url|http://violetyong.blogspot.com/}} <br /> {{url|https://www.facebook.com/violet.yong.1}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Violet Yong Wui Wui''' ({{zh|s=\u6768\u8587\u8bb3|t=\u694a\u8587\u8af1|p=Y\u00e1ng W\u0113ihu\u00ec}}) is a [[Malaysians|Malaysian]] [[lawyer]] and [[politician]] from the [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) currently serving as the [[Deliberative assembly|assemblywoman]] of the [[Sarawak State Assembly]] for [[Pending (state constituency)|Pending]] constituency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ictu.tmp.sarawak.gov.my/seg.php?recordID=M0055&contentID=SM0112 |title=Sarawak Government Official Portal |website=Ictu.tmp.sarawak.gov.my |date= |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dunsarawak.blogspot.my/2009/03/kawasan-pilihanraya-n_4294.html |title=Dewan Undangan Negeri Sarawak |website=Dunsarawak.blogspot.my |date=2004-02-26 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref> She won the seat of N10 Pending for three consecutive terms, in the Sarawak state elections of 2006, 2011 and 2016.\n\n==Education==\nYong is a holder of [[Bachelor of Laws]] from [[University of Melbourne]], [[Australia]].<ref name=\"biodata\">{{cite web|url=http://library.perdana.org.my/Digital_Content/Serials/EDGE/2006-JAN/Eastern%20promise%20%5B41%5D.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 7, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531231450/http://library.perdana.org.my/Digital_Content/Serials/EDGE/2006-JAN/Eastern%20promise%20%5B41%5D.pdf |archivedate=May 31, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nYong is a practicing lawyer at Chong Brothers Advocates, [[Kuching]] which is owned by [[Ministry of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs]], DAP [[Sarawak]] Chairperson and [[Stampin (federal constituency)|Stampin]] [[Member of Parliament]] (MP), [[Chong Chieng Jen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sarawak-advocates.org.my/index.php/rolls-a-directories/legal-firms/86-chong-brothers-advocates |title=Chong Brothers Advocates. (Kuching) |website=Sarawak-advocates.org.my |date=2016-04-06 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nYong's initiation to [[politics]] began as a child. As a first-hand witness to politics, she tagged along with her parents, active [[Democratic Action Party|DAP]] members, to party activities and while they helped with canvassing during state elections.<ref name=\"biodata\"/>\n\nYong joined the [[Democratic Action Party]] at the age of 29 after graduating from [[Melbourne]]. In early 2005, some party leaders in the state lobbied for her to be a candidate.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2011/01/31/woman-of-substance/ |title=Woman of substance - Community &#124; The Star Online |website=Thestar.com.my |date=2011-01-31 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\nHer big win came in the [[2006 Sarawak state election]] when she won the seat of [[Pending (state constituency)]], which was considered to be an [[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]] stronghold since 1991. From then on, she has continued to gain substantial majority in the ensuing state elections for her constituency.\n\nWithin her political party, she also heads the Women's Affairs department.<ref name=\"biodata\"/>\n\nYong is sometimes associated with the [[moniker]] \"Cili Padi\" or [[Bird's eye chilli]] in English due to her pluckiness at voicing out problems and issues affecting the people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2fVxc6NCumA |title=DAP Ceramah by YB Violet Yong a.k.a. Cili Padi part 1 |publisher=YouTube |date=2013-05-02 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n===Sarawak State Election, 2006===\nYong pulled off one of the biggest upsets in the [[2006 Sarawak state election]] when she defeated [[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]] secretary general [[Malay titles#Datuk|Datuk]] [[Sim Kheng Hui]] with a majority of 4,372 votes.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/09/21/dr-sim-weve-three-names-for-pending/ |title=Dr Sim: We\u2019ve three names for Pending \u2013 BorneoPost Online &#124; Borneo , Malaysia, Sarawak Daily News &#124; Largest English Daily In Borneo |website=Theborneopost.com |date=2015-09-21 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/print/malaysia/former-classmates-to-lock-horns-in-pending |title=Former classmates to lock horns in Pending &#124; Malaysia |publisher=Malay Mail Online |date=2016-05-04 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref> Before he was defeated in 2006, Datuk Sim had been assemblyman of [[Pending (state constituency)]] since 1991.\n\n===Sarawak State Election, 2011===\nIn the [[2011 Sarawak state election]], Yong received 14,375 votes and won with a majority of 7,595 votes. She defeated Dr. [[Sim Kui Hian]] from [[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]] under [[Barisan Nasional]] who received 6,780 votes.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2011/03/07/dr-sim-to-resign-from-health-dept-soon/ |title=Dr Sim to resign from Health Dept soon - Community &#124; The Star Online |website=Thestar.com.my |date=2011-03-07 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n===Sarawak State Election, 2016===\nIn the [[2016 Sarawak state election]], Violet Yong won the seat of N10 [[Pending (state constituency)]] for a third term against incoming [[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]] candidate [[Milton Foo Tiang Wee]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsarawaktribune.com/news/56084/3-corner-fight-in-Padungan-and-Batu-Lintang-straight-fight-in-Pending/ |title=3-corner fight in Padungan and Batu Lintang, straight fight in Pending |newspaper=[[New Sarawak Tribune]] |date= |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:90%\"\n|+ '''[[Sarawak State Legislative Assembly]]'''\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Government\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Valid ballots\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n||'''[[2006 Sarawak state election|2006]]'''\n|rowspan=\"3\"|'''[[Pending (state constituency)|Pending]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Violet Yong Wui Wui'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|11,632\n|61.57\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n||Sim Kheng Hui ([[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]] / [[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|7,260\n||38.43\n||18,892\n||4,372\n||19,203\n|-\n||'''[[2011 Sarawak state election|2011]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Violet Yong Wui Wui'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|14,375\n|67.95\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n||Dr. [[Sim Kui Hian]] ([[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]] / [[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|6,780\n||32.05\n||21,155\n||7,595\n||21,310\n|-\n||'''[[2016 Sarawak state election|2016]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Violet Yong Wui Wui'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|12,454\n|62.60\n|rowspan=1 {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n||[[Milton Foo Tiang Wee]] ([[Sarawak United Peoples' Party|SUPP]] / [[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|7,442\n||37.40\n||19,896\n||5,012\n||20,038\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pending (state constituency)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yong, Violet}}\n[