{"title_page": "Kelvin Yii Lee Wuen", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Yu (Chinese surname)|Yii (\u4fde)]]}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Physician|Dr.]]\n| name = Kelvin Yii Lee Wuen\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n| native_name = {{nobold|\u4fde\u5229\u6587}}\n| native_name_lang = zh-my\n| image = \n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| constituency_MP = [[Bandar Kuching (federal constituency)|Bandar Kuching]]\n| parliament = Malaysian\n| predecessor = [[Chong Chieng Jen]] ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]-[[Pakatan Rakyat|PR]])\n| majority = 35,973 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n| term_start = 10 May 2018\n| nationality = {{MAS}}\n| citizenship = Malaysian\n| party = [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP)\n| otherparty = [[People's Pact]] (PR)<br />[[Alliance of Hope]] (PH)\n| occupation = [[Politician]]\n| profession = \n| alma_mater= [[University of London]]<br />[[Volgograd State Medical University]]\n| birth_name = Kelvin Yii Lee Wuen\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1986|08|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Kuching]], [[Sarawak]], Malaysia\n| residence = [[Kuching]], [[Sarawak]], Malaysia\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| relations =\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n[[Physician|Dr.]] '''Kelvin Yii Lee Wuen''' ({{zh|t=|s=\u4fde\u5229\u6587|p=Y\u016b L\u00ecw\u00e9n}}; born 31 August 1986),<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=17 November 2018|url=https://calon.ubah.my/?page=candidate_profile&state=sarawak&code=P195|title=P195 BANDAR KUCHING|publisher=[[Democratic Action Party]]}}</ref> is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] [[politician]] from the [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) currently serving as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) of [[Parliament of Malaysia|Malaysia]] representing [[Bandar Kuching (federal constituency)|Bandar Kuching]] constituency. Concurrently, he also sits on the [[Budget Select Committee (Malaysia)|Budget Select Committee]] and is special assistant to [[Chong Chieng Jen]], [[Stampin (federal constituency)|Stampin]] MP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/454684|publisher=[[Malaysiakini]]|accessdate=26 April 2019|title=Six new select committees announced, Anwar heads reforms caucus|date=4 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://mms2018.malaysianmedics.org/yb-dr-kelvin-yii-lee-wuen/|accessdate=17 November 2018|title=YB Dr Kelvin Yii Lee Wuen|date=2018|publisher=Malaysian Medical Summit 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2020, Yii tested positive for [[COVID-19]] and was quarantined at [[Sarawak General Hospital]]. He was suspected of having been infected with the virus after meeting [[Sarikei (federal constituency)|Sarikei]] MP [[Wong Ling Biu]] who was also tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.malaysiakini.com/news/515041|title=Bandar Kuching MP Kelvin Yii tests positive for Covid-19|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|work=Malaysiakini}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nYii graduated from the [[University of London]] with a [[Bachelor of Laws]] (LL.B.) before furthering his studies and obtained a [[Doctor of Medicine]] (MD) degree from the [[Volgograd State Medical University]] in [[Volgograd]], [[Russia]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nCurrently, he is in his final thesis for [[Master of Laws]] (LL.M.) in [[Medical law|Medical Law]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:90%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]'''\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|[[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]]\n|'''P195 [[Bandar Kuching (federal constituency)|Bandar Kuching]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Kelvin Yii Lee Wuen'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party|'''DAP''']])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|48,548\n|79.43%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Kho Teck Wan ([[Sarawak United People's Party|SUPP]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|12,575\n|20.57%\n|61,483\n|35,973\n|75.11%\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Budget Select Committee (Malaysia)]]\n* [[Bandar Kuching (federal constituency)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Sarawak-FedRep}}\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yii, Kelvin Lee Wuen}}\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Democratic Action Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:People from Kuching]]\n[[Category:People from Sarawak]]\n[[Category:Malaysian politicians of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n[[Category:Sarawak politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n\n\n{{Malaysia-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Yu (Chinese surname)|Yii (\u4fde)]]}}\n\n{{Infobox MP\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Physician|Dr.]]\n| name = Kelvin Yii Lee Wuen\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n| native_name = {{nobold|\u4fde\u5229\u6587}}\n| native_name_lang = zh-my\n| image = \n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| constituency_MP = [[Bandar Kuching (federal constituency)|Bandar Kuching]]\n| parliament = Malaysian\n| predecessor = [[Chong Chieng Jen]] ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]-[[Pakatan Rakyat|PR]])\n| majority = 35,973 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n| term_start = 10 May 2018\n| nationality = {{MAS}}\n| citizenship = Malaysian\n| party = [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP)\n| otherparty = [[People's Pact]] (PR)<br />[[Alliance of Hope]] (PH)\n| occupation = [[Politician]]\n| profession = \n| alma_mater= [[University of London]]<br />[[Volgograd State Medical University]]\n| birth_name = Kelvin Yii Lee Wuen\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1986|08|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Kuching]], [[Sarawak]], Malaysia\n| residence = [[Kuching]], [[Sarawak]], Malaysia\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| relations =\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n[[Physician|Dr.]] '''Kelvin Yii Lee Wuen''' ({{zh|t=|s=\u4fde\u5229\u6587|p=Y\u016b L\u00ecw\u00e9n}}; born 31 August 1986),<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=17 November 2018|url=https://calon.ubah.my/?page=candidate_profile&state=sarawak&code=P195|title=P195 BANDAR KUCHING|publisher=[[Democratic Action Party]]}}</ref> is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] [[politician]] from the [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) currently serving as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) of [[Parliament of Malaysia|Malaysia]] representing [[Bandar Kuching (federal constituency)|Bandar Kuching]] constituency. Concurrently, he also sits on the [[Budget Select Committee (Malaysia)|Budget Select Committee]] and is special assistant to [[Chong Chieng Jen]], [[Stampin (federal constituency)|Stampin]] MP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/454684|publisher=[[Malaysiakini]]|accessdate=26 April 2019|title=Six new select committees announced, Anwar heads reforms caucus|date=4 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://mms2018.malaysianmedics.org/yb-dr-kelvin-yii-lee-wuen/|accessdate=17 November 2018|title=YB Dr Kelvin Yii Lee Wuen|date=2018|publisher=Malaysian Medical Summit 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2020, Yii tested positive for [[COVID-19]] and was quarantined at [[Sarawak General Hospital]]. He was suspected of having been infected with the virus after meeting [[Sarikei (federal constituency)|Sarikei]] MP [[Wong Ling Biu]] who was also tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.malaysiakini.com/news/515041|title=Bandar Kuching MP Kelvin Yii tests positive for Covid-19|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|work=Malaysiakini}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nYii graduated from the [[University of London]] with a [[Bachelor of Laws]] (LL.B.) before furthering his studies and obtained a [[Doctor of Medicine]] (MD) degree from the [[Volgograd State Medical University]] in [[Volgograd]], [[Russia]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nCurrently, he is in his final thesis for [[Master of Laws]] (LL.M.) in [[Medical law|Medical Law]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:90%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]'''\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|[[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]]\n|'''P195 [[Bandar Kuching (federal constituency)|Bandar Kuching]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Kelvin Yii Lee Wuen'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party|'''DAP''']])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|48,548\n|79.43%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Kho Teck Wan ([[Sarawak United People's Party|SUPP]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|12,575\n|20.57%\n|61,483\n|35,973\n|75.11%\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Budget Select Committee (Malaysia)]]\n* [[Bandar Kuching (federal constituency)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Sarawak-FedRep}}\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yii, Kelvin Lee Wuen}}\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Democratic Action Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:People from Kuching]]\n[[Category:People from Sarawak]]\n[[Category:Malaysian politicians of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian people]]\n[[Category:Sarawak politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n\n{{Malaysia-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "duplicate categorization; already in subcat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin_Yii_Lee_Wuen"}
{"title_page": "Hannah Yeoh", "text_new": "{{short description|Malaysian politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Yang (surname)|Yeoh (\u6768)]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other salutations|Puan]]\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n| name             = Hannah Yeoh\n| native_name      = {{nobold|\u6768\u5de7\u53cc}}\n| native_name_lang = zh-my\n| image            = First woman and youngest Speaker of any legislative assembly in Malaysia.jpg\n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Hannah Yeoh Tseow Suan\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1979|01|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Subang Jaya, Malaysia]]\n| residence        = \n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| office           = [[Minister of Women and Family Development (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Women, Family and Community Development]]\n| monarch          = [[Muhammad V of Kelantan|Muhammad V]]<br/>[[Abdullah of Pahang|Abdullah]]\n| primeminister    = [[Mahathir Mohamad]]\n| minister         = [[Wan Azizah Wan Ismail]]\n| term_start       = 2 July 2018\n| term_end         = 24 February 2020\n| predecessor      = [[Azizah Mohd Dun]]<br />{{small|(Women and Family Development)}}<br />[[Chew Mei Fun]]<br />{{small|(Community)}}\n| successor        = [[Siti Zailah Mohd Yusoff]]\n| constituency     = [[Segambut]]\n| office2          = 10th [[Speaker of Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]\n| term_start2      = 21 June 2013\n| term_end2        = 9 April 2018\n| predecessor2     = [[Teng Chang Khim]]\n| successor2       = [[Ng Suee Lim]]\n| constituency_MP3 = [[Segambut (federal constituency)|Segambut]]\n| parliament3      = Malaysian\n| majority3        = 45,702 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n| term_start3      = 10 May 2018\n| term_end3        = \n| predecessor3     = [[Lim Lip Eng]] ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]-[[Pakatan Rakyat|PR]])\n| successor3       = \n| constituency_AM4 = [[Subang Jaya (state constituency)|Subang Jaya]]\n| assembly4        = Selangor State Legislative\n| majority4        = 28,069 ([[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]])<br/>13,851 ([[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]])\n| term_start4      = 8 March 2008\n| term_end4        = 9 April 2018\n| predecessor4     = [[Lee Hwa Beng]] ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor4       = [[Michelle Ng Mei Sze]] ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]-[[Pakatan Harapan|PH]])\n| party            = [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP)\n| otherparty       = [[Pakatan Rakyat]] (PR)<br />[[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH)\n| occupation       = [[Politician]]\n| profession       = [[Lawyer]]\n| relations        = \n| spouse           = Ramanchandran Muniandy\n| children         = 2 daughters\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Tasmania]]\n| website          = {{URL|http://www.hannahyeoh.com/}}\n| footnotes        = \n}}\n\n'''Hannah Yeoh Tseow Suan''' ({{zh|t=\u694a\u5de7\u96d9|s=\u6768\u5de7\u53cc|p=Y\u00e1ng Qi\u01ceoshu\u0101ng}}; born 9 January 1979) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] [[politician]] from the [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) currently serving as the [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) of [[Parliament of Malaysia|Malaysia]] for [[Segambut (federal constituency)|Segambut]] constituency in [[Kuala Lumpur]].\n\nYeoh is also the former [[Speaker of Selangor State Legislative Assembly|Speaker]] and a two-term assemblywoman of the [[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]] for [[Subang Jaya (state constituency)|Subang Jaya]] constituency. Yeoh is also the former Deputy Minister of Women, Family and Community Development.\n\n==Background==\nBorn in Subang Jaya, Yeoh studied at SK Sri Subang Jaya, SRK SS19 and SMK Subang Utama, after which she continued her studies at the University of Tasmania in Australia and obtained her law degree in 2001. She was recognized as a lawyer by the [[Malaysian Bar]] in January 2003 and was subsequently admitted to the Supreme Court of Tasmania after obtaining a Certificate of Legal Practice in Tasmania. Yeoh then served as a lawyer in Petaling Jaya for three years before moving to the ceremony management company in 2006.\n\n==Political career==\nDriven by Edward Ling, her schoolmate, to join the world of politics, both Yeoh and Ling joined the Damansara [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) Branch in the late 2006. Yeoh opted to join the DAP even though the party was an opposition party as she felt that the stand of the political party is the most consistent, though its leaders are often threatened by the [[Internal Security Act (Malaysia)|Internal Security Act]] which allows for arrest without any trial.\n\nInspired by [[Tony Pua]], Damansara Branch Chairman, who resigned to join DAP full-time, Yeoh followed Pua's footsteps and resigned shortly before the March 2008 general election to devote her full-time as a politician.\n\nYeoh was elected as the Selangor state assemblyperson for the seat of Subang Jaya in the [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008 general election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2008/03/10/billi-takes-defeat-in-his-stride/|title=Billi takes defeat in his stride|date=10 March 2008|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|publisher=Star Publications|accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref><ref>Lourdes, Mark. [http://hwabeng.org.my/node/960 \"'Handyman' wants to move.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20070808080510/http://hwabeng.org.my/node/960 |date=8 August 2007 }}, ''New Straits Times'' (Hosted on Lee Hwa Beng's Blog), 13 February 2008. Retrieved on 2008-06-27.</ref> In the [[2013 Malaysian general election|2013 general election]], Yeoh was re-elected as Subang Jaya state assembly person for the second term. After her re-election, on 21 June 2013 she was sworn in as Malaysia's first woman speaker for Selangor State Assembly.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.malaysiandigest.com/news/81182-hannah-yeoh-sworn-in-as-countrys-first-woman-state-speaker.html|title=Hannah Yeoh Sworn In As Country's First Woman State Speaker|date=21 June 2013|work=Malaysian Digest|publisher=malaysiandigest.com|accessdate=22 Jun 2013}}</ref> At the age of 34 she is also the youngest speaker of any legislative Assembly in Malaysia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2013/06/22/yeoh-is-malaysias-youngest-and-first-female-state-speaker/|title=Yeoh is Malaysia's youngest and first female state Speaker|date=22 June 2013|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|publisher=Star Publications|accessdate=22 Jun 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 general election]], Yeoh was picked by DAP to run for the [[Segambut (federal constituency)|Segambut]] parliamentary seat and she successfully won it. When Pakatan Harapan took over the government, she was appointed as the Deputy Minister of Women, Family, and Community Development in the new Malaysian cabinet.\n\n==Personal life==\nYeoh has 4 siblings, she is a former [[lawyer]] and event manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sinchew.com.my/node/1772123/|title=\u8c8c\u4f3c\u6155\u5c24\u4e01- \u2027- \u6b23\u8d4f\u90ed\u7d20\u6c81\u2014\u2014\u6768\u5de7\u53cc\u7236\u4eb2\u662f\u6587\u9752|date=2018-07-08|publisher=[[Sin Chew Daily]]}}</ref> She is married to Ramanchandran Muniandy with whom she has two daughters, Shay Adora Ram and Kayleigh Imani Ram.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hannahyeoh.blogspot.hk/p/my-profile.html |title=Hannah Yeaoh:My Profile |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date=31 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402121924/http://www.hannahyeoh.blogspot.hk/p/my-profile.html |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]''': [[Subang Jaya (state constituency)|Subang Jaya]]<ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php|title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]]|accessdate=27 May 2010}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://resultpru13.spr.gov.my/module/keputusan/paparan/paparan_laporan.php |title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM 13|work=Sistem Pengurusan Maklumat Pilihan Raya Umum|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]]|language=Malay|accessdate=24 March 2017}}Results only available for the [[2013 Malaysian general election|2013 election]].</ref><ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{cite web|url=http://undi.info/#|title=Malaysian Election Data|publisher=[[Malaysiakini]]|accessdate=12 May 2013}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"GE14 results\">{{cite web|url=https://keputusan.spr.gov.my/|title=SEMAKAN KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM KE - 14|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=17 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref> \n!|Year\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2| Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|[[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Hannah Yeoh'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party|'''DAP''']])\n|align=\"right\" |23,459\n|70.94%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Ong Chong Suan ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]])\n|align=\"right\" |9,608\n|29.06%\n|33,067\n|13,851\n|79.31%\n|-\n|[[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Hannah Yeoh'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party|'''DAP''']])\n|align=\"right\" |40,366\n|76.09%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Gan Meng Foo ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]])\n|align=\"right\" |12,297\n|23.17%\n|53,052\n|28,069\n|86.20%\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]''': [[Segambut (federal constituency)|Segambut]]<ref name=\"undiinfo\"/>\n!|Year\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2| Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballot cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{nowrap|'''Hannah Yeoh'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party (Malaysia)|'''DAP''']])\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 53,124\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 82.07%\n| {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Loga Bala Mohan  ([[People's Progressive Party (Malaysia)|MyPPP]])\n| 7,422\n| 11.47%\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 77,956\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 45,702\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 83.72%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|Mohd Solleh Abd Razak ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n| 4,181\n| 6.46%\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Segambut (federal constituency)]]\n* [[Subang Jaya (state constituency)]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{URL|http://www.hannahyeoh.com/}}\n\n{{Malaysian Ministers}}\n{{KualaLumpur-FedRep}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yeoh, Hannah}}\n[[Category:Malaysian lawyers]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:People from Kuala Lumpur]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Democratic Action Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:Women MLAs in Selangor]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Christians]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:University of Tasmania alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Malaysian women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Women legislative speakers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Malaysian politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Yang (surname)|Yeoh (\u6768)]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other salutations|Puan]]\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n| name             = Hannah Yeoh\n| native_name      = {{nobold|\u6768\u5de7\u53cc}}\n| native_name_lang = zh-my\n| image            = First woman and youngest Speaker of any legislative assembly in Malaysia.jpg\n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Hannah Yeoh Tseow Suan\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1979|01|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Subang Jaya, Malaysia]]\n| residence        = \n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| office           = [[Minister of Women and Family Development (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Women, Family and Community Development]]\n| monarch          = [[Muhammad V of Kelantan|Muhammad V]]<br/>[[Abdullah of Pahang|Abdullah]]\n| primeminister    = [[Mahathir Mohamad]]\n| minister         = [[Wan Azizah Wan Ismail]]\n| term_start       = 2 July 2018\n| term_end         = 24 February 2020\n| predecessor      = [[Azizah Mohd Dun]]<br />{{small|(Women and Family Development)}}<br />[[Chew Mei Fun]]<br />{{small|(Community)}}\n| successor        = [[Siti Zailah Mohd Yusoff]]\n| constituency     = [[Segambut]]\n| office2          = 10th [[Speaker of Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]\n| term_start2      = 21 June 2013\n| term_end2        = 9 April 2018\n| predecessor2     = [[Teng Chang Khim]]\n| successor2       = [[Ng Suee Lim]]\n| constituency_MP3 = [[Segambut (federal constituency)|Segambut]]\n| parliament3      = Malaysian\n| majority3        = 45,702 ([[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]])\n| term_start3      = 10 May 2018\n| term_end3        = \n| predecessor3     = [[Lim Lip Eng]] ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]-[[Pakatan Rakyat|PR]])\n| successor3       = \n| constituency_AM4 = [[Subang Jaya (state constituency)|Subang Jaya]]\n| assembly4        = Selangor State Legislative\n| majority4        = 28,069 ([[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]])<br/>13,851 ([[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]])\n| term_start4      = 8 March 2008\n| term_end4        = 9 April 2018\n| predecessor4     = [[Lee Hwa Beng]] ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor4       = [[Michelle Ng Mei Sze]] ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]-[[Pakatan Harapan|PH]])\n| party            = [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP)\n| otherparty       = [[Pakatan Rakyat]] (PR)<br />[[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH)\n| occupation       = [[Politician]]\n| profession       = [[Lawyer]]\n| relations        = \n| spouse           = Ramanchandran Muniandy\n| children         = 2 daughters\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Tasmania]]\n| website          = {{URL|http://www.hannahyeoh.com/}}\n| footnotes        = \n}}\n\n'''Hannah Yeoh Tseow Suan''' ({{zh|t=\u694a\u5de7\u96d9|s=\u6768\u5de7\u53cc|p=Y\u00e1ng Qi\u01ceoshu\u0101ng}}; born 9 January 1979) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] [[politician]] from the [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) currently serving as the [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) of [[Parliament of Malaysia|Malaysia]] for [[Segambut (federal constituency)|Segambut]] constituency in [[Kuala Lumpur]].\n\nYeoh is also the former [[Speaker of Selangor State Legislative Assembly|Speaker]] and a two-term assemblywoman of the [[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]] for [[Subang Jaya (state constituency)|Subang Jaya]] constituency. Yeoh is also the former Deputy Minister of Women, Family and Community Development.\n\n==Background==\nBorn in Subang Jaya, Yeoh studied at SK Sri Subang Jaya, SRK SS19 and SMK Subang Utama, after which she continued her studies at the University of Tasmania in Australia and obtained her law degree in 2001. She was recognized as a lawyer by the [[Malaysian Bar]] in January 2003 and was subsequently admitted to the Supreme Court of Tasmania after obtaining a Certificate of Legal Practice in Tasmania. Yeoh then served as a lawyer in Petaling Jaya for three years before moving to the ceremony management company in 2006.\n\n==Political career==\nDriven by Edward Ling, her schoolmate, to join the world of politics, both Yeoh and Ling joined the Damansara [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) Branch in the late 2006. Yeoh opted to join the DAP even though the party was an opposition party as she felt that the stand of the political party is the most consistent, though its leaders are often threatened by the [[Internal Security Act (Malaysia)|Internal Security Act]] which allows for arrest without any trial.\n\nInspired by [[Tony Pua]], Damansara Branch Chairman, who resigned to join DAP full-time, Yeoh followed Pua's footsteps and resigned shortly before the March 2008 general election to devote her full-time as a politician.\n\nYeoh was elected as the Selangor state assemblyperson for the seat of Subang Jaya in the [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008 general election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2008/03/10/billi-takes-defeat-in-his-stride/|title=Billi takes defeat in his stride|date=10 March 2008|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|publisher=Star Publications|accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref><ref>Lourdes, Mark. [http://hwabeng.org.my/node/960 \"'Handyman' wants to move.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20070808080510/http://hwabeng.org.my/node/960 |date=8 August 2007 }}, ''New Straits Times'' (Hosted on Lee Hwa Beng's Blog), 13 February 2008. Retrieved on 2008-06-27.</ref> In the [[2013 Malaysian general election|2013 general election]], Yeoh was re-elected as Subang Jaya state assembly person for the second term. After her re-election, on 21 June 2013 she was sworn in as Malaysia's first woman speaker for Selangor State Assembly.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.malaysiandigest.com/news/81182-hannah-yeoh-sworn-in-as-countrys-first-woman-state-speaker.html|title=Hannah Yeoh Sworn In As Country's First Woman State Speaker|date=21 June 2013|work=Malaysian Digest|publisher=malaysiandigest.com|accessdate=22 Jun 2013}}</ref> At the age of 34 she is also the youngest speaker of any legislative Assembly in Malaysia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2013/06/22/yeoh-is-malaysias-youngest-and-first-female-state-speaker/|title=Yeoh is Malaysia's youngest and first female state Speaker|date=22 June 2013|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|publisher=Star Publications|accessdate=22 Jun 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 general election]], Yeoh was picked by DAP to run for the [[Segambut (federal constituency)|Segambut]] parliamentary seat and she successfully won it. When Pakatan Harapan took over the government, she was appointed as the Deputy Minister of Women, Family, and Community Development in the new Malaysian cabinet.\n\n==Personal life==\nYeoh has 4 siblings, she is a former [[lawyer]] and event manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sinchew.com.my/node/1772123/|title=\u8c8c\u4f3c\u6155\u5c24\u4e01- \u2027- \u6b23\u8d4f\u90ed\u7d20\u6c81\u2014\u2014\u6768\u5de7\u53cc\u7236\u4eb2\u662f\u6587\u9752|date=2018-07-08|publisher=[[Sin Chew Daily]]}}</ref> She is married to Ramanchandran Muniandy with whom she has two daughters, Shay Adora Ram and Kayleigh Imani Ram.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hannahyeoh.blogspot.hk/p/my-profile.html |title=Hannah Yeaoh:My Profile |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date=31 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402121924/http://www.hannahyeoh.blogspot.hk/p/my-profile.html |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]''': [[Subang Jaya (state constituency)|Subang Jaya]]<ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php|title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]]|accessdate=27 May 2010}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://resultpru13.spr.gov.my/module/keputusan/paparan/paparan_laporan.php |title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM 13|work=Sistem Pengurusan Maklumat Pilihan Raya Umum|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]]|language=Malay|accessdate=24 March 2017}}Results only available for the [[2013 Malaysian general election|2013 election]].</ref><ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{cite web|url=http://undi.info/#|title=Malaysian Election Data|publisher=[[Malaysiakini]]|accessdate=12 May 2013}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"GE14 results\">{{cite web|url=https://keputusan.spr.gov.my/|title=SEMAKAN KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM KE - 14|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=17 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref> \n!|Year\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2| Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|[[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Hannah Yeoh'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party|'''DAP''']])\n|align=\"right\" |23,459\n|70.94%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Ong Chong Suan ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]])\n|align=\"right\" |9,608\n|29.06%\n|33,067\n|13,851\n|79.31%\n|-\n|[[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Hannah Yeoh'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party|'''DAP''']])\n|align=\"right\" |40,366\n|76.09%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Gan Meng Foo ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]])\n|align=\"right\" |12,297\n|23.17%\n|53,052\n|28,069\n|86.20%\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]''': [[Segambut (federal constituency)|Segambut]]<ref name=\"undiinfo\"/>\n!|Year\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2| Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballot cast\n!|Majority\n!|T