{"title_page": "Yeo Bee Yin", "text_new": "{{short description|Malaysian politician}}\n{{chinese name|[[Yang (surname)|Yeo (\u6768)]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary style|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other salutations|Puan]]\n| name = Yeo Bee Yin\n| native_name = {{nobold|\u6768\u7f8e\u76c8}}\n| native_name_lang = zh-my\n| honorific-suffix = {{small|[[Member of Parliament|MP]]}}\n| image = YB_Yeo_Bee_Yin.png\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Yeo Bee Yin, in 2018\n| birth_name = Yeo Bee Yin\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1983|05|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Segamat]], [[Johor]], [[Malaysia]]\n| residence = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| office = [[Minister of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change (Malaysia)|Minister of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change]]\n| monarch = [[Muhammad V of Kelantan|Muhammad V]]<br/>[[Abdullah of Pahang|Abdullah]]\n| primeminister = [[Mahathir Mohamad]]\n| term_start = 2 July 2018\n| term_end = 24 February 2020\n| deputy = [[Isnaraissah Munirah Majilis]]\n| predecessor = 1. [[Wilfred Madius Tangau]] (Science, Technology) <br /> 2. [[Maximus Ongkili]] (Energy) <br /> 3. [[Wan Junaidi]] (Environment)\n| successor = 1. [[Khairy Jamaluddin]] (Science, Technology and Innovation) <br /> 2. [[Shamsul Anuar Nasarah]] (Energy)  <br /> 3. [[Tuan Ibrahim Tuan Man]] (Environment)\n| constituency = [[Bakri (federal constituency)|Bakri]]\n| citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| constituency_MP2 = [[Bakri (federal constituency)|Bakri]], Johor\n| parliament2 = Malaysian\n| term_start2 = 9 May 2018\n| term_end2 = \n| majority2 = 23,211 [[2018 Malaysian general election|(2018)]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Er Teck Hwa]] ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]\u2014[[Pakatan Harapan|PH]])\n| successor2 = \n| constituency_AM3 = [[Damansara Utama (state constituency)|Damansara Utama]]<br /><small>(renamed Bandar Utama)</small>\n| assembly3 = Selangor State\n| majority3 = \n| term_start3 = 6 May 2013\n| term_end3 = 9 May 2018\n| predecessor3 = Cheah Wing Yin ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]\u2013[[Pakatan Rakyat|PR]])\n| successor3 = Jamaliah Jamaluddin ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]\u2013[[Pakatan Harapan|PH]]) \n| constituency3 = \n| party = [[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]\n| occupation = Politician\n| profession = Field engineer\n| majority = \n| relations = \n| spouse = Lee Yeow Seng\n| partner         = \n| children = \n| alma_mater = [[National Junior College]] <br /> [[Universiti Teknologi Petronas]] <br /> [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]\n| website = {{URL|yeobeeyin.blogspot.com}}\n| footnotes = {{facebook|yeobeeyin}}<br>{{pom|3669}}\n| module = {{Chinese |child=yes|t=\u694a\u7f8e\u76c8|s=\u6768\u7f8e\u76c8|p=Y\u00e1ng M\u011biy\u00edng}}\n}}\n'''Yeo Bee Yin''' ({{zh|s=\u6768\u7f8e\u76c8|t=\u694a\u7f8e\u76c8|p=Y\u00e1ng M\u011biy\u00edng}}; born 26 May 1983) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician from the [[Democratic Action Party (Malaysia)|Democratic Action Party]] (DAP), a component party in the [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) ruling coalition. Yeo was the former [[Minister of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change (Malaysia)|Minister of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change]]. She is also the incumbent [[Dewan Rakyat|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Bakri (federal constituency)|Bakri]] in [[Johor]]. Previously she was the former Member of the [[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]] for the [[Damansara Utama (state constituency)|Damansara Utama]] state seat for one term from 2013 to 2018.\n\n==Personal life==\nYeo was born on 26 May 1983, and started growing up in Gomali Estate before moving to a small town, [[Batu Anam]] in [[Segamat]] at the northern part of Johor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yeobeeyin.com/p/my-story.html|title=Yeo Bee Yin \u6768\u7f8e\u76c8: My Story|website=Yeo Bee Yin \u6768\u7f8e\u76c8 Blog|accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nYeo was married on 11 March 2019 to Lee Yeow Seng, the chief executive officer of IOI Properties Group Bhd.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/03/30/when-the-stars-finally-aligned-for-yeo-and-lee/|title=When the stars finally aligned for Yeo and Lee|publisher=[[The Star Online]]|work=[[Sin Chew Daily]]|author=|date=30 March 2019|access-date=30 March 2019}}</ref> Lee is also the youngest son of the founder and boss of [[IOI Group]]; tycoon Tan Sri [[Lee Shin Cheng]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/03/11/yeo-bee-yin-ties-the-knot-with-property-ceo/|title=Yeo Bee Yin ties the knot with property CEO|publisher=[[The Star Online]]|work=[[Sin Chew Daily]]|author=|date=11 March 2019|access-date=11 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nYeo graduated from [[Universiti Teknologi Petronas]] (UTP) with First Class Honors in Chemical Engineering under the Petronas Scholarship in 2006. After two years working with [[Schlumberger]], she went on to pursue an MPhil (Masters in Philosophy) in Advanced Chemical Engineering at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge|Corpus Christi College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], under the [[Gates Cambridge Scholarship]] by the [[Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation]], and completed her degree with a Commendation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gatescambridge.org/members-area/connect/directory/scholar/6292|title=Profile - Miss Bee Yin Yeo (2009)|work=[[University of Cambridge]]|publisher=[[Gates Cambridge Scholarship|Gates Cambridge]]|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"academic\">{{cite news|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/leisure/2016/03/01/class-acts-the-academic-backgrounds-of-15-msian-leaders/|title=Class acts: The academic backgrounds of 15 M'sian leaders|author=Jafwan Jaafar|publisher=[[Free Malaysia Today]]|date=1 March 2016|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political career and experience==\nYeo had been volunteering for DAP since February 2012 before joining the party permanently with another academician, Dr [[Ong Kian Ming]], in August the same year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Make Way for the Pakatan Women \u2013 Part 1|url=http://www.therocket.com.my/en/yeo-bee-yin/|accessdate=25 May 2013|newspaper=Roketkini|date=6 November 2012}}</ref> While running her own business, she was also the social media strategic advisor to the party,<ref>{{cite web|title=GE13: New-face Yeo hopes to apply what she has learnt|url=http://thestar.com.my/metro/story.asp?file=/2013/4/26/central/13014197&sec=central|work=Yip Yoke Teng|publisher=The Star (Malaysia)|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref> as well as special assistant to [[Tony Pua]], the MP of [[Petaling Jaya Utara (federal constituency)|Petaling Jaya Utara]].\n\nShe is also the National Assistant Publicity Secretary of the DAP, Vice Chairperson of [[Pakatan Harapan]] Youth, and Political Education Director of DAP Wanita Selangor.<ref name=\"Blog\">{{cite web|url=http://www.yeobeeyin.com/p/about-me.html|title=Yeo Bee Yin \u6768\u7f8e\u76c8: About Me|website=Yeo Bee Yin \u6768\u7f8e\u76c8 Blog|accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament for Bakri (May 2018 - present)==\nYeo was picked by DAP to contest in the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 general election]] (GE14) as the Pakatan Harapan candidate for the [[Bakri, Johor|Bakri]] parliamentary seat in Johor<ref>{{cite news|title=DAP names Yeo Bee Yin as candidate for Bakri seat|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/03/24/dap-names-yeo-bee-yin-as-candidate-for-bakri-seat/|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|date=24 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2018}}</ref> and successfully elected to the [[Parliament of Malaysia|Parliament]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.awanireview.com/articles/2018/05/30/news/bakri-mp-yeo-bee-yin-i-had-a-dream-to-build-a-better-malaysia-347/|title=MALAYSIA BAHARU: Bakri MP Yeo Bee Yin: I Had a Dream \u2013 To Build a Better Malaysia|author=Isabelle Leong|work=Awani Rreview|publisher=Astro Awani|date=|accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Minister of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change ==\nYeo was appointed and sworn in as Minister of Energy, Technology, Science, Climate Change and Environment on 2 July 2018, as part of [[Prime Minister of Malaysia|Prime Minister]] [[Seventh Mahathir cabinet|Mahathir's 7th Cabinet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/02/new-ministers-being-sworn-in-before-king/|title=New ministers sworn in before King (updated) - Nation {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2018-07-02}}</ref> The ministry was later renamed as [[Ministry of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change (Malaysia)|Ministry of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change]] (MESTECC) on 2 August 2018 for acronym convenience purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2018/08/399529/mestecc-ministry-energy-science-technology-environment-and-climate-change|title=Mestecc is ministry of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change|agency=Bernama|date=August 8, 2018|website=New Straits Times|accessdate=September 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAmongst her early actions as minister was to announce an increase of renewable energy goals from 2% to 20% by 2030.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2018/11/435126/govt-optimistic-achieving-20-pct-re-over-next-seven-years|title=Govt optimistic of achieving 20 pct RE over next seven years|agency=Bernama|first=|date=27 November 2018|work=New Straits Time|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/business/2018/09/412551/20pc-target-re-efficiency-may-take-longer-expected|title=20pc target of RE efficiency may take longer than expected|last=Zakariah|first=Zarina|date=18 September 2018|work=New Straits Times|access-date=}}</ref>  She has also initiated a refurbishment of government buildings to lead on efficient energy consumption.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/11/01/yeo-malaysia-can-save-at-least-rm47bil-over-15-years/|title=Yeo: Malaysia can save at least RM47bil over 15 years by being more energy efficient|last=Carvalho|first=Martin|date=1 Nov 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nShe has helped to set up a nationwide ban on the import of plastic waste<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2018/10/421727/malaysia-and-asean-not-dumping-ground-advanced-countries|title=Malaysia and ASEAN not dumping ground for advanced countries|last=Abdul Karim|first=Luqman Arif|date=16 October 2018|work=New Straits Times|access-date=}}</ref> and published a 12 year roadmap that includes a legal framework in eliminating the use of single use plastics in Malaysia by 2030.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mestecc.gov.my/web/en/documents/39q_GhHr7Yf6i1n620DjKU9RZlz3jnBa3oj5YhGOuFg,|title=Malaysia Roadmap Towards Zero Single Use Plastics 2018-2030|last=MESTECC|date=2018|website=MESTECC}}</ref>  Within a few short months as minister, her work on the environment had already garnered recognition from the journal ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]''.<ref name=\"Nature's 10\">{{cite web\n  | author =  Yao-Hua Law\n  | title = Nature's 10 :Ten people who mattered this year - BEE YIN YEO: Force for the environment\n  | work = [[Nature's 10]]\n  | publisher = [[Nature (journal)|Nature]]\n  | language = \n  | date = 20 December 2018\n  | url = https://www.nature.com/immersive/d41586-018-07683-5/index.html\n  | accessdate = 18 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===\"Roadmap Towards Zero Single-Use Plastic\" 2018\u20132030===\nAccording to a scientific study published in the journal ''Science'' in 2015, Malaysia is ranked 8th in mismanaged plastic wastes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.star2.com/living/2018/03/25/plastic-waste-pollution|title=Malaysia's The 8th Worst Country Worldwide For Plastic Waste|last=Mangai Balasegaram|first=|date=25 March 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref> Mismanagement of plastic waste will impact the environment, health and economy of the country. There are also plastics that will decompose into micro-plastic that can enter the food chain and affect aquatic life and human health.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/how-microplastics-make-their-way-up-the-ocean-food-chain-into-fish-69148|title=How Micro-plastic Make Their Way Up The Ocean Food Chain Into Fish|date=1 December 2016|work=The Conversation|access-date=}}</ref> Therefore, Malaysia Roadmap Towards Zero Single-Use Plastic by 2030 launched in October 2018 is a guideline for the nation to implement actions in phases for the next 12 years leading to 2030.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/content/news-msia-breaks-plastics-zero-singleuse-plastics-roadmap-0|title=M'sia breaks up with plastics with zero single-use plastics roadmap|last=The Edge Markets|first=|date=17 October 2018|work=The Edge Markets|access-date=}}</ref> The roadmap is a living document which allows the state governments to roll out the initiatives and implementation of policies according to each state level of awareness and readiness within the time frame set by MESTECC.\n\n===Cancellation of Four IPPs===\nThe Malaysian Government has decided to cancel four [[Independent Power Producer]] (IPP)s' contracts, awarded through direct negotiations, for failing to adhere to conditions stipulated in the respective offer letters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/putrajaya-cancels-4-ipp-projects-says-yeo|title=Putrajaya cancels 4 IPP projects, says Yeo|last=Surin Murigiah|first=|date=25 October 2018|work=The Edge Markets|access-date=}}</ref> This announcement was made in a reply by Minister of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change Yeo Bee Yin to a question from Ipoh Timur MP [[Wong Kah Woh]] in Parliament on 25 October 2018.\n\nThe four cancelled IPPs were Malakoff Corp Bhd and [[Tenaga Nasional|Tenaga Nasional Bhd]]'s 700MW gas powered plant in Kapar, Selangor; Aman Majestic Sdn Bhd and Tenaga Nasional's 1,400MW plant in Paka, Terengganu; Sabah Development Energy (Sandakan) Sdn Bhd and SM Hydro Energy Sdn Bhd hydropower plant at the Palm Oil Industrial Cluster (POIC) in Sandakan, Sabah and The solar power quota of 400MW to Edra Power Holdings Sdn Bhd for the utilisation of solar power plant.\n\nIf the national electric reserve margin remained at the optimal 32% and if these projects were allowed to continue, it would increase the reserve margin to 46%, which is a level above what is required.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/power-reserve-margin-hit-46-if-no-ipp-projects-axed|title=Power reserve margin to hit 46% if no IPP projects axed|last=Chester Tay|first=|date=7 August 2018|work=The Edge Market|access-date=}}</ref>  When capacity payments increase, so will the electric bills. The cancellations had allowed the Government to achieve a savings of RM1.26 billion in electric supply.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/10/25/termination-of-four-ipp-projects-could-save-rm1bil-in-electricity-tariffs/|title=Termination of four IPP projects could save RM1.26bil in electricity tariffs,says Minister|last=Martin Carvalho, Rahimy Rahim and Clarissa Chung|first=|date=25 October 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Feed-in Tariff (Fit) Quota Revocation and New Quota Release===\nA total of 156MW (155.7256MW) renewable energy quota revoked in September 2018 allowing for 115MW (114.5682MW) on offer in the fourth quarter of 2018. The quota will be opened for application in batches.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://mrem.bernama.com/viewsm.php?idm=32984 |title=Minister TB Yeo Bee Yin Announces Revocation Of Non-Performing Feed-In Tariff Projects And New Quota Release By SEDA In Q4 2018 |agency=Bernama |date=17 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe mini hydro will have a quota of 74.5682 MW for application expected to achieve commercial operations by 2020 and 2021. The quota allocated for biogas and biomass are 30MW and 10MW respectively; these quota are for applications achieving commercial operations by 2021.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2018/10/18/nonperforming-feedin-tariff-projects-revoked/|title= Non-performing Feed-in Tariff projects revoked|last=Corporat News|date=18 October 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThat is the first time Sustainable Energy Development Authority (SEDA) had opens the e-bidding for biogas in Feed in Tariff system aiming to create better pricing efficiency for electricity generated from the biogas resources through healthy competition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2018/10/18/nonperforming-feedin-tariff-projects-revoked/|title=Non-performing Feed-in Tariff projects revoked|last=Corporate News|date=18 October 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Solar PV Initiatives - Improvement of Net Energy Metering (NEM) and Solar Leasing===\nTowards the end of 2016, the Malaysian Government had introduced the Net Energy Metering(NEM) programme to encourage installation of rooftop Solar PV to generate renewable energy for consumption and to export back to the grid and the producer-consumers will be paid back with the displaced cost through the electricity bill.\n\nThe quota that was determined in 2016 was 500MW for the period of 5 years from 2016 to 2020. The breakdown was 120MW for domestic users, 195MW for commercial and 185MW for industrial. However, two years after the launched the uptake rate was very low at about 17MW or 3.4%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/10/22/from-jan-1-solar-power-users-to-enjoy-cheaper-electricity-bills/|title=From Jan 1, solar power users to enjoy cheaper electricity bills|last=Martin Carvalho, Hemananthani Sivanandam and Rahimy Rahim|date=22 October 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nTo improve the implementation of NEM, the MESTECC implemented initiatives for domestic, commercial and industrial users.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/solar-power-producers-enjoy-better-rebates-tnb-next-year|title=Consumers producing solar power to enjoy better rebates from TNB next year|last=Adam Aziz|date=23 October 2018|work=The Edge Financial Daily|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFor domestic users, the Government will improve NEM by allowing the additional energy that is generated to be exported back to the grid, on a one-to-one offset. This means every 1kWh generated will be off-set against 1 kWh utilized by the customer, instead of at the previously quoted displaced costs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/beginning-2019-no-price-difference-between-solar-generation-and-consumption-tariff|title=Beginning 2019, no price difference between solar generation and consumption tariff|last=Adam Aziz|date=22 October 2018|work=The Edge Markets|access-date=}}</ref> Through this initiative, MESTECC hopes the uptake for the NEM will increase as subsequently reduces the cost of energy for domestic users.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/10/22/from-jan-1-solar-power-users-to-enjoy-cheaper-electricity-bills/|title=From Jan 1, solar power users to enjoy cheaper electricity bills|last=Martin Carvalho,Hemananthani Sivanandam and Rahimy Rahim|date=22 October 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFor the commercial and industrial users, the Government has agreed to implement NEM through the solar leasing mechanism using the Supply Agreement for Renewable Energy (SARE).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nemsolarmalaysia.com/sare-malaysia/|title=Supply Agreement of Renewable Energy (SARE) Malaysia|last=NEM Solar Malaysia|date=2019|work=NEM Solar Malaysia|access-date=}}</ref> Through this method, the cost for purchasing and installation of Solar PVs, electricity generation revenue, and electricity tariff will be agreed upon by three parties between Customers, Investors/Owners of PV Panels and the utility company (TNB). This initiative frees the customers from paying for the upfront cost.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pv-tech.org/news/malaysias-tnb-offers-solar-packages-to-businesses-and-homes|title=Boost for Malaysian PV market as utility giant offers zero upfront solar|last=Tom Kenning|date=19 October 2018|work=PV Tech|access-date=}}</ref> The installation and Solar PV cost will be borne by Investors and utility company.\n\nNEM was first implemented at the end of 2016 and the total approved capacity as at end 2018, was 27.81 MW.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/seda-midst-completing-ebidding-biogas-small-hydro-power|title=SEDA in midst of completing e-bidding for biogas, small hydro power|last=Chester Tay|date=23 July 2019|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref> Since January 2019, the NEM scheme was enhanced to allow surplus solar electricity to be sold on a 1-on-1 basis. To date, SEDA Malaysia has approved up to 58.6 MW under the enhanced NEM programme.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.edgeprop.my/content/1569419/seda-allows-property-developers-reserve-nem-quota-new-projects-aug-5|title=SEDA allows property developers reserve NEM quota for new projects from Aug 5|agency=Bernama|date=5 August 2019|work=Edge Prop|access-date=4 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Open Tender for Large Scale Solar Projects (LSS3)===\nIn February 2019, the Malaysia government had called for bids for RM2 billion worth of projects under the third round of the large-scale solar (LSS3) scheme to increase electricity generation from renewable energy. The competitive bidding process was opened for a six-month period from February to August 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/yeo-bee-yin-malaysia-opens-tender-rm2b-largescale-solar-power-projects|title=Malaysia opens tender for RM2b large-scale solar power projects|last=Tan Xue Ying|date=15 February 2019|work=theedgemarkets|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the LSS3 bidding which ended in August 2019, saw the cost of generating per kilowatt-hour (kWh) from solar energy was lower than energy generation from natural gas sources because of improvements in technology and the adoption of open bidding for power projects.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2019/09/04/open-bidding-bringing-down-cost-of-generating-renewable-energy|title=Open Bidding Brings Down Cost of Generating Renewable Energy|last=the star|date=4 September 2019|work=thestar|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref> The four lowest bids, which encompassed 365 MW out of 500 MW, came below the current cost of gas-fired power generation of 23.22 sen per kWh, with the lowest bid being 17.77 sen per kWh. This marks a 45% reduction from the lowest price of 32 sen per kWh for the second round of the Large Solar Project (LSS2) bid a few years ago.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/business/2019/09/518422/malaysia-needs-rm33b-investment-hit-renewable-energy-target-yeo|title=Malaysia needs RM33b investment to hit renewable energy target - Yeo|agency=Bernama|date=4 September 2019|work=nst|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nYeo is expecting that the upcoming 500MW plant would likely close below 24 sen per kWh, pending technical evaluation. Malaysia will see a more competitive and diversified power generation mix as technological advances in renewable energy and rising demand have made the access to the technology cheaper, contributing to a lower cost of electricity generation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.edgeprop.my/content/1582557/solar-electricity-cheaper-produce-yeo-says-lss3-bid-closes|title=Solar electricity cheaper to produce, Yeo says as LSS3 bid closes|last=Tan Xue Ying|date=3 September 2019|work=theedgemarkets|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nYeo also noted that Malaysia needed investments totalling RM33 billion in order to achieve its target of 20 percent electricity generation from renewable energy sources by 2025.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/malaysia-needs-rm33b-investment-to-hit-renewable-energy-target-yeo-HE1327180 |title=Malaysia needs RM33b investment to hit renewable energy target: Yeo |agency=[[Bernama]] |date=3 September 2019 |work=thesundaily}}</ref> Meantime, the Securities Commission has conducted a six-month study on green financing by forming a task force to provide a report on 21 action items for the facilitation of the RM33 billion investments into renewable energy. The Malaysian Government is committed to continue the current incentives for green investment for example Green Technology Financing Scheme, Green Investment Tax Allowance and Green Income Tax Exemption.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://themalaysianreserve.com/2019/09/04/latest-solar-farm-bids-lowest-at-17-8-sen/|title=Latest solar farm bids lowest at 17.8 sen |first1=Alifah |last1=Zainuddin |date=4 September 2019 |work=The Malaysian Reserve }}</ref>\n\n===The Second Biogas E-bidding Exercise and The First E-bidding for Small Hydro Power Systems===\nSustainable Energy Development Authority (SEDA) Malaysia is completing second biogas e-bidding exercise and inaugural e-bidding for small hydro power systems.\n\nIn a statement dated 23 July 2019, Yeo said the aim of the e-bidding process is to facilitate price discovery for renewable energy (RE) generated from biogas and small hydro resources, through healthy competition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/seda-midst-completing-ebidding-biogas-small-hydro-power|title=SEDA in midst of completing e-bidding for biogas, small hydro power|last=Chester Tay|date=23 July 2019|work=The Edge Markets|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nFeed-in Tariff (FiT) scheme had traditionally offered tariff at fixed rate. Having implemented the FiT for seven years, SEDA had improved price discovery of the tariff offered to renewable energy developer by way of competitive bidding. The inaugural e-bidding exercise for biogas was carried out in the fourth quarter of 2018. The schedule of e-bidding under the current phase includes 30MW and 160MW for biogas and small hydro respectively.\n\nAs at end of June 2019, SEDA approved 12,540 Feed-in Tariff (FiT) applications with a total capacity of 1,744.38 MW. This comprised 34.6 percent (small hydro), 25.4 percent (solar PV), 23.5 percent (biomass), 14.4 percent (biogas) and 2.1 percent (geothermal).\n\nMeanwhile, the total RE projects achieving commercial operation was 10,254 with total installed capacity of 621.96 MW (61.8 percent solar PV, 15.4 percent biomass, 11.5 percent biogas and 11.3 percent small hydro.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/business/2019/07/506652/seda-complete-second-biogas-e-bidding-exercise-and-small-hydro-power-systems|title=SEDA to complete second biogas e-bidding exercise and small hydro power systems|last=NST|date=23 July 2019|work=New Straits Times|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Energy Efficiency and Conservation Act (EECA)===\nA joint study by the Malaysian Government's Economic Planning Unit (EPU) and the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) estimated that Malaysia had potential energy savings of up RM46.92 billion from 2016 to 2030. The study shows that the main obstacle from widespread use of energy efficient practices is the lack of regulatory framework.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2018/11/01/minister-study-shows-energy-efficiency-could-unlock-rm47b-savings-over-15-y/1688894|title=Minister: Study shows energy efficiency could unlock RM47b savings over 15 years|last=Azril Annuar|date=1 November 2018|work=Malay Mail|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref> Therefore, MESTECC is working on the framework for the Energy Efficiency and Conservation Act (EECA), the act is expected to be tabled in the Dewan Rakyat at the end of 2019.<ref name=\"Bernama\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/07/04/energy-efficiency-and-conservation-bill-to-be-tabled-end-of-this-year-minis/1768303|title=Energy Efficiency and Conservation Bill to be tabled end of this year, says minister|agency=Bernama|date=4 July 2019|work=Malay Mail|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Energy Performance Contract (EPC)===\nApart from drafting the Energy Efficiency and Conservation Act, MESTECC has also reviewed and improved the National Energy Efficiency Action Plan (NEEAP) 2016-2025 and has set a new target to achieve at least 8 percent saving through energy efficiency by 2025.<ref name=\"Bernama\"/>\nMESTECC will focus on energy efficiency in the building sector as it has been identified internationally as one of the most cost-effective sectors to reduce energy consumption.\n\nBuilding electricity consumption comprises more than 50 percent of the electricity consumption in Malaysia.This shows that there is a great potential for cost savings if Malaysia can improve energy efficiency in buildings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://themalaysianreserve.com/2018/11/02/energy-efficiency-to-save-govt-nearly-rm47b-by-2030/|title=Energy efficiency to save govt nearly RM47b by 2030|last= P PREM KUMAR & ALIFAH ZAINUDDIN |date=2 November 2019|work=The Malaysian Reserve|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Decision on Accumulated Radioactive Residue at Lynas Advanced Materials Plant in Gebeng, Kuantan===\nFollowing the Executive Review Committee on Operations of [[Lynas#Lynas Advanced Materials Plant|Lynas Advance Material Plants]] (LAMP) in Gebeng which was presented to the MESTECC as scheduled on 27 November 2018, the Ministry is concerned with the increasing risk arising from the continued accumulation of residue without a viable solution to manage its accumulation in the near-term.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/mestecc-disallows-unlimited-accumulation-of-residual-waste-at-lynas-plant-GB210190|title=MESTECC disallows unlimited accumulation of residual waste at Lynas plant|agency=Bernama|date=4 December 2018|work=The Sun Daily|access-date=}}</ref> For this reason, the Ministry will not allow the unlimited accumulation of residue at LAMP.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/12/04/lynas-review-recommends-permanent-disposal-facility/|title=Lynas review recommends permanent disposal facility, Ministry says residue must be removed from Malaysia|last=Ong Han Sean|date=4 December 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn this regard, the following pre-conditions will be applied to Lynas Malaysia for future licences/permission renewals:\n# The accumulated WLP residue, which contains radioactive materials, must be removed from Malaysia. (Note: the existing temporary storage licence expires on 2 September 2019.) The Ministry notes that Lynas Corporation Ltd., Australia (Lynas Australia) and Lynas Malaysia Sdn. Bhd. (Lynas Malaysia) had each presented letters of undertaking dated 23 February 2012 and 6 March 2012 respectively indicating their commitment to remove LAMP residue from Malaysia, if necessary.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/ministry-lynas-must-remove-radioactive-residue-malaysia|title=Ministry: Lynas must remove radioactive residue from Malaysia|last=Supriya Surendran|date=5 December 2018|work=The Edge Markets|access-date=}}</ref> \n# For the non-radioactive NUF scheduled waste, LAMP shall submit an action plan on the disposal of its accumulated wastes before it will be considered for future applications under Rule 9 (6) and 9 (7) of the Environmental Quality Regulations (Scheduled Waste) 2005. (Note: the current approval for the storage of scheduled wastes is valid until 15 February 2019).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/s/1699974/no-unlimited-storage-of-waste-for-lynas-says-ministry|title=No unlimited storage of waste for Lynas, says ministry|last= Emmanuel Santa Maria Chin|date=4 December 2018|work=Malay Mail|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Ministry is confident that this decision will help further ensure the well-being of the community and the environment.\n\n==Selangor State Assembly Representative for Damansara Utama (June 2013 - April 2018)==\n[[File:Yeo Bee Yin, 2013 (cropped).jpg|left|thumb|Yeo Bee Yin, in GE13]]\nIn the [[2013 Malaysian general election|2013 general election]] (GE13), Yeo contested for the first time and won the [[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]] constituency for Damansara Utama on a DAP ticket with 83.6% of the votes and a 30,689 majority, the highest majority for state seats in Malaysia. She was the youngest member of the  [[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]] then.<ref name=\"Blog\"/> Following her election, Yeo said that her main priorities were decreasing the high crime rates, traffic jams, as well as combating flash floods and poverty issues.<ref>{{cite news|last=Prasena|first=Priscilla|title=New rep vows openness|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2013/05/22/new-rep-vows-openness/|accessdate=25 May 2013|newspaper=[[Free Malaysia Today]]|date=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Rosmah and PERMATA ===\nIn March 2017, Yeo questioned the finances of the [[PERMATApintar National Gifted Center|PERMATApintar]] (commonly known just as PERMATA) programme, a child education and welfare programme, of which Prime Minister [[Najib Razak]]'s wife, [[Rosmah Mansor]] is the patron, urging for the transparency of the organisation's financial accounts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/357632|title=Rakyat has right to full picture of Permata, presses Yeo|date=2016-10-02|work=Malaysiakini|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref>\n\nYeo also questioned the need for a separate agency under the Prime Minister's Department with Rosmah, an individual not elected by the people, to have such a significant role in government, saying that early childhood development programmes such as PERMATA should be under the respective full ministries which are more equipped and have the personnel with more experience in the field.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/03/15/let-relevant-ministry-take-over-permata-dap-tells-rosmah/|title=Let relevant ministry take over Permata, DAP tells Rosmah|date=2017-03-15|work=Free Malaysia Today|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017 SMUE misappropriation allegation ===\nIn March 2017, Jamal Mohd Yunos, the [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO) Sungai Besar division chief had alleged that funds from the Selangor state government for the Skim Mesra Usia Emas (SMUE) had been misappropriated by Yeo. Yeo disproved the allegation with documents showing each SMUE payment made.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/03/22/dap-rep-refutes-funds-misuse-allegation-by-jamal-yunos/|title=DAP rep refutes funds misuse allegation by Jamal Yunos|date=2017-03-22|work=Free Malaysia Today|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref> Yeo appeared at the [[Malaysian Anti-Corruption Commission]] (MACC) office where Jamal was expected to show up to lodge a report. Yeo brought along a mirror with the words \"Nothing to Hide\" written on it to be presented to Jamal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/03/24/mirror-mirror-on-jamals-wall/|title=Mirror, mirror on Jamal's wall|date=2017-03-24|work=Free Malaysia Today|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref> Jamal however did not appear to lodge his report and the mirror was instead handed to his representative. Subsequently, Yeo filed a RM5 million suit against Jamal for defamation, in which, Jamal failed to appear at the High Court case management.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/07/13/jamal-yunos-no-show-in-court-for-libel-suit-by-yeo/|title=Jamal Yunos no-show in court for libel suit by Yeo|date=2017-07-13|work=Free Malaysia Today|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref>\n\n=== MCA Kampung Cempaka, Petaling Jaya land dispute ===\nIn September 2017, DAP lawmakers questioned the [[Malaysian Chinese Association]] (MCA) of Selangor about a one-acre plot of land in Kampung Cempaka, Petaling Jaya which was allegedly purchased under market price.\n\nMCA had applied for the land in 2006 and got approval from the state government in 2007 (which was then under Barisan Nasional). MCA then bought the land at RM 52,000 in 2008 at RM 1 per square foot (psf), when the land in fact was worth more than RM400psf. Yeo later on discovered the MCA's plans to convert the land to commercial status earlier in the year. She questioned the methods of how MCA managed to purchase the land under market price.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/s/14648/|title=DAP wants MCA to explain Petaling Jaya land buy {{!}} The Malaysian Insight|website=www.themalaysianinsight.com|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref> When the former [[Petaling Jaya Utara (federal constituency)|Petaling Jaya Utara]] MP, [[Chew Mei Fun]] of MCA was contacted on the matter, she denied being involved in the land application and declined to explain further.\n\nAfter the case was exposed to public knowledge, three MCA leaders - MCA Selangor Vice Chairperson Tang Song Chang, Chew and current MCA PJU division chief Tan Gim Tuan came forward to justify that the 1acre plot of land bought under market price will be used for public service. Yeo refuted this claim, explaining that if the land was actually for public service, then there would be no need for MCA to own the land as public service lands should be owned by the state government. Yeo also requested for proof or guarantee that MCA intended the land to be used for public service, and also further questioned the reason MCA applied for the land to be rezoned and converted from a \"water body\" to \"commercial land\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/09/29/yeo-to-mca-pj-land-to-be-used-for-public-services-really/|title=Yeo to MCA: PJ land to be used for public services \u2013 really?|date=2017-09-29|work=Free Malaysia Today|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref>\n\nChew later threatened to sue Yeo and/or the DAP Member of Parliament for Petaling Jaya Utara then, [[Tony Pua]], to which the DAP leaders openly welcomed, holding on to their standing that they had not done anything defamatory towards Chew or the MCA by revealing truthful facts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/395678|title=Feel free to sue us, DAP reps tell MCA veep|date=2017-09-19|work=Malaysiakini|access-date=2018-03-07}}</ref>\n\n===Charity works===\nYeo's office runs two tuition centres in Damansara Bistari and Kampung Chempaka, which offer free classes for students between the ages of 7 to 17 from low-income families.<ref>{{Citation|last=ZAP Film|title=Pusat Tuisyen Rakyat Selangor|date=2016-07-18|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O834h1grhms|accessdate=2018-03-06}}</ref> She also runs a monthly [[food bank]] program providing basic necessities assistance to more than 100 people.\n\nShe also works with DAP's Impian Malaysia movement, being one of the pioneers of the first Impian Sarawak project in Kampung Sait, [[Sarawak]] which works to provide basic infrastructure such as roads, water, and electricity in Sarawak.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2016/03/15/real-change-means-working-on-the-impossible/|title=Real change means working on the impossible|author=Mikha Chan|publisher=[[Free Malaysia Today]]|date=15 March 2016|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe is the founder of LEAP (Leadership, Education, Activism and Politics), which aims to educate students on the political process and activism in Malaysia, such as the formation of political parties, [[election campaign]]s, constituency management, media relations, coalition formation and debates.<ref name=\"academic\"/>\n\nShe is also the founder of the Lawatan Anak Muda (LAM) Programme which allows young participants to visit the Malaysian Parliament and the Selangor State Assembly. Participants get the chance to have a Q&A session with a few Members of Parliament and state assemblypersons.<ref>{{Cite news\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | title = Yeo Bee Yin's Lawatan Anak Muda (LAM) Programme\n  | publisher = Yeo Bee Yin\uff08\u6768\u7f8e\u76c8\uff09Facebook\n  | language = ms\n  | date = 8 November 2017 \n  | url = https://business.facebook.com/yeobeeyin/posts/938841036269822?comment_id=938988902921702&comment_tracking=%7B%22tn%22%3A%22R0%22%7D\n  | accessdate = 23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n<ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=4 February 2017 }} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+'''[[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]''': N36 [[Damansara Utama (state constituency)|Damansara Utama]]<ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{cite web\n  | title = Malaysia General Election \n  | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data\n  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]\n  | url = http://undi.info/#\n  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://resultpru13.spr.gov.my/module/keputusan/paparan/paparan_laporan.php|title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM 13|work=Sistem Pengurusan Maklumat Pilihan Raya Umum|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n!|Year\n! colspan=\"2\" |Government\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n! colspan=\"2\" |Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{nowrap|'''Yeo Bee Yin'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party|'''DAP''']])\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:right;\" |'''37,303'''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |'''84.21%'''\n| {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Lim Choon Kin ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |6,614\n|14.93%\n| rowspan=\"2\" |44,654\n| rowspan=\"2\" |30,689\n| rowspan=\"2\" |83.63%\n|-\n| {{Party shading/Independent}} |\n| Liew Wei Beng ([[Independent politician|IND]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 380\n| 0.86%\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+'''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]''': P145 [[Bakri (federal constituency)|Bakri]], Johor.<ref name=\"undiinfo\"/><ref name=\"GE14 results\">{{cite web|url=https://keputusan.spr.gov.my/|title=SEMAKAN KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM KE - 14|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=17 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"The Star GE14\">{{cite web|url=https://election.thestar.com.my/|title=The Star Online GE14|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=24 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref>\n!|Year\n!colspan=2|Government \n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{nowrap|'''Yeo Bee Yin''' ([[Democratic Action Party (Malaysia)|'''DAP''']])}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:right;\"|'''38,718''' \n| rowspan=\"2\" | '''62.65%'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Koh Chon Chai ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]])\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|15,507 \n|25.09%\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 61,800\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 23,211\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 84.50%\n|-\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|{{nowrap|Md Zahrul Salleh ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|7,575 \n|12.26%\n|}\n\n==Awards and recognitions==\n===International Honours===\n*[[Nature's 10]] - \"Top 10 People Who Mattered in Science 2018\" - By [[Nature (journal)|Nature]], a [[United Kingdom|British]] international journal focusing on scientific and technological research.<ref name=\"Nature's 10\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/12/20/science-journal-hails-yeo-bee-yin-as-a-force-for-environment/|title=Science journal hails Yeo Bee Yin as a 'force for environment'|publisher=[[The Star Online]]|author= |date=20 December 2018|access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news\n  | author =  Iylia Adreena\n  | title = Minister Yeo Bee Yin Is The Top 10 Most Important People In Science For 2018\n  | publisher = [[MSN]]\n  | language = \n  | date = 20 December 2018 \n  | url = https://www.msn.com/en-my/news/national/minister-yeo-bee-yin-is-the-top-10-most-important-people-in-science-for-2018/ar-BBRd8dT?li=BBr8Mk9\n  | accessdate = 18 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news\n  | author = Kwan Ling\n  | title = UK-Based Scientific Journal Names Yeo Bee Yin One of Top 10 People Who Impacted the World\n  | publisher = WORLD OF BUZZ\n  | language = \n  | date = 20 December 2018 \n  | url = https://www.worldofbuzz.com/uk-based-scientific-journal-names-yeo-bee-yin-one-of-top-10-people-who-impacted-world/\n  | accessdate = 18 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n*7 people who stood up for our planet in 2018 - By Eco-Business, a leading digital media company serving Asia Pacific\u2019s clean technology, smart cities, responsible business and sustainable development community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eco-business.com/news/7-people-who-stood-up-for-our-planet-in-2018/|title=Yeo Bee Yin, 'sue us if you dare'|publisher=Eco-Business|author=|date=10 December 2018|access-date=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n*25 inspirational female climate leaders - \"25 female climate leaders shaping 2019\"-By [[The Ecologist]] a [[United Kingdom|British]] environmental journal, then magazine, it addressed a wide range of environmental subjects and promoted an ecological systems thinking approach through its news stories, investigations and opinion articles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theecologist.org/2019/mar/08/25-female-climate-leaders-shaping-2019|title=25 female climate leaders shaping 2019|publisher=[[The Ecologist]]|author=Arthur Wyns |date=8 March 2019|access-date=22 March 2019}}</ref>\n*2019 Young Global Leaders - \"127 Young Global Leaders 2019\" - By [[World Economic Forum]] <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/syed-saddiq-yeo-bee-yin-disenarai-sebagai-young-global-leaders-201045|title=Syed Saddiq, Yeo Bee Yin disenarai sebagai 'Young Global Leaders'|publisher=[[Astro Awani]]|author=Naila Huda |date=13 March 2019|access-date=22 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.weforum.org/press/2019/03/here-are-the-young-people-pushing-boundaries-and-changing-the-world-in-2019/|title=Here are the Young People Pushing Boundaries and Changing the World in 2019|publisher=World Economic Forum|author= |date=13 March 2019|access-date=22 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\nYeo launched her first book, \"Reimagining Malaysia\" on the 14th of March 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yeobeeyin.com/p/reimagining-malaysia.html|title=Reimagining Malaysia|website=www.yeobeeyin.com|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Reimagining Malaysia|last=Yeo|first=Bee Yin|publisher=Democratic Action Party|year=2018|isbn=9789839820652|location=Malaysia|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.yeobeeyin.com/ Yeo Bee Yin's blog]\n* {{facebook|yeobeeyin}}\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n\n{{Johor-FedRep}}\n{{Malaysian Ministers}}\n{{Seventh Mahathir cabinet}}\n{{Pakatan Harapan}}\n{{Portal bar|Malaysia|Biography|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yeo, Bee Yin}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:People from Johor]]\n[[Category:Malaysian politicians of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Hokkien descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian activists]]\n[[Category:Malaysian environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Malaysian women environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Malaysian engineers]]\n[[Category:Women chemical engineers]]\n[[Category:Democratic Action Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:Women in Johor politics]]\n[[Category:Members of the Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Women MLAs in Selangor]]\n[[Category:Women in Selangor politics]]\n[[Category:Universiti Teknologi Petronas alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Malaysian politician}}\n{{chinese name|[[Yang (surname)|Yeo (\u6768)]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary style|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other salutations|Puan]]\n| name = Yeo Bee Yin\n| native_name = {{nobold|\u6768\u7f8e\u76c8}}\n| native_name_lang = zh-my\n| honorific-suffix = {{small|[[Member of Parliament|MP]]}}\n| image = YB_Yeo_Bee_Yin.png\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Yeo Bee Yin, in 2018\n| birth_name = Yeo Bee Yin\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1983|05|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Segamat]], [[Johor]], [[Malaysia]]\n| residence = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| office = [[Minister of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change (Malaysia)|Minister of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change]]\n| monarch = [[Muhammad V of Kelantan|Muhammad V]]<br/>[[Abdullah of Pahang|Abdullah]]\n| primeminister = [[Mahathir Mohamad]]\n| term_start = 2 July 2018\n| term_end = 24 February 2020\n| deputy = [[Isnaraissah Munirah Majilis]]\n| predecessor = 1. [[Wilfred Madius Tangau]] (Science, Technology) <br /> 2. [[Maximus Ongkili]] (Energy) <br /> 3. [[Wan Junaidi]] (Environment)\n| successor = 1. [[Khairy Jamaluddin]] (Science, Technology and Innovation) <br /> 2. [[Shamsul Anuar Nasarah]] (Energy)  <br /> 3. [[Tuan Ibrahim Tuan Man]] (Environment)\n| constituency = [[Bakri (federal constituency)|Bakri]]\n| citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| constituency_MP2 = [[Bakri (federal constituency)|Bakri]], Johor\n| parliament2 = Malaysian\n| term_start2 = 9 May 2018\n| term_end2 = \n| majority2 = 23,211 [[2018 Malaysian general election|(2018)]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Er Teck Hwa]] ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]\u2014[[Pakatan Harapan|PH]])\n| successor2 = \n| constituency_AM3 = [[Damansara Utama (state constituency)|Damansara Utama]]<br /><small>(renamed Bandar Utama)</small>\n| assembly3 = Selangor State\n| majority3 = \n| term_start3 = 6 May 2013\n| term_end3 = 9 May 2018\n| predecessor3 = Cheah Wing Yin ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]\u2013[[Pakatan Rakyat|PR]])\n| successor3 = Jamaliah Jamaluddin ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]\u2013[[Pakatan Harapan|PH]]) \n| constituency3 = \n| party = [[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]\n| occupation = Politician\n| profession = Field engineer\n| majority = \n| relations = \n| spouse = Lee Yeow Seng\n| partner         = \n| children = \n| alma_mater = [[National Junior College]] <br /> [[Universiti Teknologi Petronas]] <br /> [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]\n| website = {{URL|yeobeeyin.blogspot.com}}\n| footnotes = {{facebook|yeobeeyin}}<br>{{pom|3669}}\n| module = {{Chinese |child=yes|t=\u694a\u7f8e\u76c8|s=\u6768\u7f8e\u76c8|p=Y\u00e1ng M\u011biy\u00edng}}\n}}\n'''Yeo Bee Yin''' ({{zh|s=\u6768\u7f8e\u76c8|t=\u694a\u7f8e\u76c8|p=Y\u00e1ng M\u011biy\u00edng}}; born 26 May 1983) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician from the [[Democratic Action Party (Malaysia)|Democratic Action Party]] (DAP), a component party in the [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) ruling coalition. Yeo was the former [[Minister of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change (Malaysia)|Minister of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change]]. She is also the incumbent [[Dewan Rakyat|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Bakri (federal constituency)|Bakri]] in [[Johor]]. Previously she was the former Member of the [[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]] for the [[Damansara Utama (state constituency)|Damansara Utama]] state seat for one term from 2013 to 2018.\n\n==Personal life==\nYeo was born on 26 May 1983, and started growing up in Gomali Estate before moving to a small town, [[Batu Anam]] in [[Segamat]] at the northern part of Johor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yeobeeyin.com/p/my-story.html|title=Yeo Bee Yin \u6768\u7f8e\u76c8: My Story|website=Yeo Bee Yin \u6768\u7f8e\u76c8 Blog|accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nYeo was married on 11 March 2019 to Lee Yeow Seng, the chief executive officer of IOI Properties Group Bhd.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/03/30/when-the-stars-finally-aligned-for-yeo-and-lee/|title=When the stars finally aligned for Yeo and Lee|publisher=[[The Star Online]]|work=[[Sin Chew Daily]]|author=|date=30 March 2019|access-date=30 March 2019}}</ref> Lee is also the youngest son of the founder and boss of [[IOI Group]]; tycoon Tan Sri [[Lee Shin Cheng]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/03/11/yeo-bee-yin-ties-the-knot-with-property-ceo/|title=Yeo Bee Yin ties the knot with property CEO|publisher=[[The Star Online]]|work=[[Sin Chew Daily]]|author=|date=11 March 2019|access-date=11 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nYeo graduated from [[Universiti Teknologi Petronas]] (UTP) with First Class Honors in Chemical Engineering under the Petronas Scholarship in 2006. After two years working with [[Schlumberger]], she went on to pursue an MPhil (Masters in Philosophy) in Advanced Chemical Engineering at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge|Corpus Christi College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], under the [[Gates Cambridge Scholarship]] by the [[Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation]], and completed her degree with a Commendation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gatescambridge.org/members-area/connect/directory/scholar/6292|title=Profile - Miss Bee Yin Yeo (2009)|work=[[University of Cambridge]]|publisher=[[Gates Cambridge Scholarship|Gates Cambridge]]|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"academic\">{{cite news|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/leisure/2016/03/01/class-acts-the-academic-backgrounds-of-15-msian-leaders/|title=Class acts: The academic backgrounds of 15 M'sian leaders|author=Jafwan Jaafar|publisher=[[Free Malaysia Today]]|date=1 March 2016|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political career and experience==\nYeo had been volunteering for DAP since February 2012 before joining the party permanently with another academician, Dr [[Ong Kian Ming]], in August the same year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Make Way for the Pakatan Women \u2013 Part 1|url=http://www.therocket.com.my/en/yeo-bee-yin/|accessdate=25 May 2013|newspaper=Roketkini|date=6 November 2012}}</ref> While running her own business, she was also the social media strategic advisor to the party,<ref>{{cite web|title=GE13: New-face Yeo hopes to apply what she has learnt|url=http://thestar.com.my/metro/story.asp?file=/2013/4/26/central/13014197&sec=central|work=Yip Yoke Teng|publisher=The Star (Malaysia)|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref> as well as special assistant to [[Tony Pua]], the MP of [[Petaling Jaya Utara (federal constituency)|Petaling Jaya Utara]].\n\nShe is also the National Assistant Publicity Secretary of the DAP, Vice Chairperson of [[Pakatan Harapan]] Youth, and Political Education Director of DAP Wanita Selangor.<ref name=\"Blog\">{{cite web|url=http://www.yeobeeyin.com/p/about-me.html|title=Yeo Bee Yin \u6768\u7f8e\u76c8: About Me|website=Yeo Bee Yin \u6768\u7f8e\u76c8 Blog|accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament for Bakri (May 2018 - present)==\nYeo was picked by DAP to contest in the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 general election]] (GE14) as the Pakatan Harapan candidate for the [[Bakri, Johor|Bakri]] parliamentary seat in Johor<ref>{{cite news|title=DAP names Yeo Bee Yin as candidate for Bakri seat|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/03/24/dap-names-yeo-bee-yin-as-candidate-for-bakri-seat/|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|date=24 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2018}}</ref> and successfully elected to the [[Parliament of Malaysia|Parliament]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.awanireview.com/articles/2018/05/30/news/bakri-mp-yeo-bee-yin-i-had-a-dream-to-build-a-better-malaysia-347/|title=MALAYSIA BAHARU: Bakri MP Yeo Bee Yin: I Had a Dream \u2013 To Build a Better Malaysia|author=Isabelle Leong|work=Awani Rreview|publisher=Astro Awani|date=|accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Minister of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change ==\nYeo was appointed and sworn in as Minister of Energy, Technology, Science, Climate Change and Environment on 2 July 2018, as part of [[Prime Minister of Malaysia|Prime Minister]] [[Seventh Mahathir cabinet|Mahathir's 7th Cabinet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/02/new-ministers-being-sworn-in-before-king/|title=New ministers sworn in before King (updated) - Nation {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2018-07-02}}</ref> The ministry was later renamed as [[Ministry of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change (Malaysia)|Ministry of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change]] (MESTECC) on 2 August 2018 for acronym convenience purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2018/08/399529/mestecc-ministry-energy-science-technology-environment-and-climate-change|title=Mestecc is ministry of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change|agency=Bernama|date=August 8, 2018|website=New Straits Times|accessdate=September 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAmongst her early actions as minister was to announce an increase of renewable energy goals from 2% to 20% by 2030.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2018/11/435126/govt-optimistic-achieving-20-pct-re-over-next-seven-years|title=Govt optimistic of achieving 20 pct RE over next seven years|agency=Bernama|first=|date=27 November 2018|work=New Straits Time|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/business/2018/09/412551/20pc-target-re-efficiency-may-take-longer-expected|title=20pc target of RE efficiency may take longer than expected|last=Zakariah|first=Zarina|date=18 September 2018|work=New Straits Times|access-date=}}</ref>  She has also initiated a refurbishment of government buildings to lead on efficient energy consumption.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/11/01/yeo-malaysia-can-save-at-least-rm47bil-over-15-years/|title=Yeo: Malaysia can save at least RM47bil over 15 years by being more energy efficient|last=Carvalho|first=Martin|date=1 Nov 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nShe has helped to set up a nationwide ban on the import of plastic waste<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2018/10/421727/malaysia-and-asean-not-dumping-ground-advanced-countries|title=Malaysia and ASEAN not dumping ground for advanced countries|last=Abdul Karim|first=Luqman Arif|date=16 October 2018|work=New Straits Times|access-date=}}</ref> and published a 12 year roadmap that includes a legal framework in eliminating the use of single use plastics in Malaysia by 2030.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mestecc.gov.my/web/en/documents/39q_GhHr7Yf6i1n620DjKU9RZlz3jnBa3oj5YhGOuFg,|title=Malaysia Roadmap Towards Zero Single Use Plastics 2018-2030|last=MESTECC|date=2018|website=MESTECC}}</ref>  Within a few short months as minister, her work on the environment had already garnered recognition from the journal ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]''.<ref name=\"Nature's 10\">{{cite web\n  | author =  Yao-Hua Law\n  | title = Nature's 10 :Ten people who mattered this year - BEE YIN YEO: Force for the environment\n  | work = [[Nature's 10]]\n  | publisher = [[Nature (journal)|Nature]]\n  | language = \n  | date = 20 December 2018\n  | url = https://www.nature.com/immersive/d41586-018-07683-5/index.html\n  | accessdate = 18 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===\"Roadmap Towards Zero Single-Use Plastic\" 2018\u20132030===\nAccording to a scientific study published in the journal ''Science'' in 2015, Malaysia is ranked 8th in mismanaged plastic wastes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.star2.com/living/2018/03/25/plastic-waste-pollution|title=Malaysia's The 8th Worst Country Worldwide For Plastic Waste|last=Mangai Balasegaram|first=|date=25 March 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref> Mismanagement of plastic waste will impact the environment, health and economy of the country. There are also plastics that will decompose into micro-plastic that can enter the food chain and affect aquatic life and human health.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/how-microplastics-make-their-way-up-the-ocean-food-chain-into-fish-69148|title=How Micro-plastic Make Their Way Up The Ocean Food Chain Into Fish|date=1 December 2016|work=The Conversation|access-date=}}</ref> Therefore, Malaysia Roadmap Towards Zero Single-Use Plastic by 2030 launched in October 2018 is a guideline for the nation to implement actions in phases for the next 12 years leading to 2030.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/content/news-msia-breaks-plastics-zero-singleuse-plastics-roadmap-0|title=M'sia breaks up with plastics with zero single-use plastics roadmap|last=The Edge Markets|first=|date=17 October 2018|work=The Edge Markets|access-date=}}</ref> The roadmap is a living document which allows the state governments to roll out the initiatives and implementation of policies according to each state level of awareness and readiness within the time frame set by MESTECC.\n\n===Cancellation of Four IPPs===\nThe Malaysian Government has decided to cancel four [[Independent Power Producer]] (IPP)s' contracts, awarded through direct negotiations, for failing to adhere to conditions stipulated in the respective offer letters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/putrajaya-cancels-4-ipp-projects-says-yeo|title=Putrajaya cancels 4 IPP projects, says Yeo|last=Surin Murigiah|first=|date=25 October 2018|work=The Edge Markets|access-date=}}</ref> This announcement was made in a reply by Minister of Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change Yeo Bee Yin to a question from Ipoh Timur MP [[Wong Kah Woh]] in Parliament on 25 October 2018.\n\nThe four cancelled IPPs were Malakoff Corp Bhd and [[Tenaga Nasional|Tenaga Nasional Bhd]]'s 700MW gas powered plant in Kapar, Selangor; Aman Majestic Sdn Bhd and Tenaga Nasional's 1,400MW plant in Paka, Terengganu; Sabah Development Energy (Sandakan) Sdn Bhd and SM Hydro Energy Sdn Bhd hydropower plant at the Palm Oil Industrial Cluster (POIC) in Sandakan, Sabah and The solar power quota of 400MW to Edra Power Holdings Sdn Bhd for the utilisation of solar power plant.\n\nIf the national electric reserve margin remained at the optimal 32% and if these projects were allowed to continue, it would increase the reserve margin to 46%, which is a level above what is required.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/power-reserve-margin-hit-46-if-no-ipp-projects-axed|title=Power reserve margin to hit 46% if no IPP projects axed|last=Chester Tay|first=|date=7 August 2018|work=The Edge Market|access-date=}}</ref>  When capacity payments increase, so will the electric bills. The cancellations had allowed the Government to achieve a savings of RM1.26 billion in electric supply.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/10/25/termination-of-four-ipp-projects-could-save-rm1bil-in-electricity-tariffs/|title=Termination of four IPP projects could save RM1.26bil in electricity tariffs,says Minister|last=Martin Carvalho, Rahimy Rahim and Clarissa Chung|first=|date=25 October 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Feed-in Tariff (Fit) Quota Revocation and New Quota Release===\nA total of 156MW (155.7256MW) renewable energy quota revoked in September 2018 allowing for 115MW (114.5682MW) on offer in the fourth quarter of 2018. The quota will be opened for application in batches.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://mrem.bernama.com/viewsm.php?idm=32984 |title=Minister TB Yeo Bee Yin Announces Revocation Of Non-Performing Feed-In Tariff Projects And New Quota Release By SEDA In Q4 2018 |agency=Bernama |date=17 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe mini hydro will have a quota of 74.5682 MW for application expected to achieve commercial operations by 2020 and 2021. The quota allocated for biogas and biomass are 30MW and 10MW respectively; these quota are for applications achieving commercial operations by 2021.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2018/10/18/nonperforming-feedin-tariff-projects-revoked/|title= Non-performing Feed-in Tariff projects revoked|last=Corporat News|date=18 October 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThat is the first time Sustainable Energy Development Authority (SEDA) had opens the e-bidding for biogas in Feed in Tariff system aiming to create better pricing efficiency for electricity generated from the biogas resources through healthy competition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2018/10/18/nonperforming-feedin-tariff-projects-revoked/|title=Non-performing Feed-in Tariff projects revoked|last=Corporate News|date=18 October 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Solar PV Initiatives - Improvement of Net Energy Metering (NEM) and Solar Leasing===\nTowards the end of 2016, the Malaysian Government had introduced the Net Energy Metering(NEM) programme to encourage installation of rooftop Solar PV to generate renewable energy for consumption and to export back to the grid and the producer-consumers will be paid back with the displaced cost through the electricity bill.\n\nThe quota that was determined in 2016 was 500MW for the period of 5 years from 2016 to 2020. The breakdown was 120MW for domestic users, 195MW for commercial and 185MW for industrial. However, two years after the launched the uptake rate was very low at about 17MW or 3.4%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/10/22/from-jan-1-solar-power-users-to-enjoy-cheaper-electricity-bills/|title=From Jan 1, solar power users to enjoy cheaper electricity bills|last=Martin Carvalho, Hemananthani Sivanandam and Rahimy Rahim|date=22 October 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nTo improve the implementation of NEM, the MESTECC implemented initiatives for domestic, commercial and industrial users.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/solar-power-producers-enjoy-better-rebates-tnb-next-year|title=Consumers producing solar power to enjoy better rebates from TNB next year|last=Adam Aziz|date=23 October 2018|work=The Edge Financial Daily|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFor domestic users, the Government will improve NEM by allowing the additional energy that is generated to be exported back to the grid, on a one-to-one offset. This means every 1kWh generated will be off-set against 1 kWh utilized by the customer, instead of at the previously quoted displaced costs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/beginning-2019-no-price-difference-between-solar-generation-and-consumption-tariff|title=Beginning 2019, no price difference between solar generation and consumption tariff|last=Adam Aziz|date=22 October 2018|work=The Edge Markets|access-date=}}</ref> Through this initiative, MESTECC hopes the uptake for the NEM will increase as subsequently reduces the cost of energy for domestic users.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/10/22/from-jan-1-solar-power-users-to-enjoy-cheaper-electricity-bills/|title=From Jan 1, solar power users to enjoy cheaper electricity bills|last=Martin Carvalho,Hemananthani Sivanandam and Rahimy Rahim|date=22 October 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFor the commercial and industrial users, the Government has agreed to implement NEM through the solar leasing mechanism using the Supply Agreement for Renewable Energy (SARE).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nemsolarmalaysia.com/sare-malaysia/|title=Supply Agreement of Renewable Energy (SARE) Malaysia|last=NEM Solar Malaysia|date=2019|work=NEM Solar Malaysia|access-date=}}</ref> Through this method, the cost for purchasing and installation of Solar PVs, electricity generation revenue, and electricity tariff will be agreed upon by three parties between Customers, Investors/Owners of PV Panels and the utility company (TNB). This initiative frees the customers from paying for the upfront cost.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pv-tech.org/news/malaysias-tnb-offers-solar-packages-to-businesses-and-homes|title=Boost for Malaysian PV market as utility giant offers zero upfront solar|last=Tom Kenning|date=19 October 2018|work=PV Tech|access-date=}}</ref> The installation and Solar PV cost will be borne by Investors and utility company.\n\nNEM was first implemented at the end of 2016 and the total approved capacity as at end 2018, was 27.81 MW.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/seda-midst-completing-ebidding-biogas-small-hydro-power|title=SEDA in midst of completing e-bidding for biogas, small hydro power|last=Chester Tay|date=23 July 2019|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref> Since January 2019, the NEM scheme was enhanced to allow surplus solar electricity to be sold on a 1-on-1 basis. To date, SEDA Malaysia has approved up to 58.6 MW under the enhanced NEM programme.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.edgeprop.my/content/1569419/seda-allows-property-developers-reserve-nem-quota-new-projects-aug-5|title=SEDA allows property developers reserve NEM quota for new projects from Aug 5|agency=Bernama|date=5 August 2019|work=Edge Prop|access-date=4 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Open Tender for Large Scale Solar Projects (LSS3)===\nIn February 2019, the Malaysia government had called for bids for RM2 billion worth of projects under the third round of the large-scale solar (LSS3) scheme to increase electricity generation from renewable energy. The competitive bidding process was opened for a six-month period from February to August 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/yeo-bee-yin-malaysia-opens-tender-rm2b-largescale-solar-power-projects|title=Malaysia opens tender for RM2b large-scale solar power projects|last=Tan Xue Ying|date=15 February 2019|work=theedgemarkets|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the LSS3 bidding which ended in August 2019, saw the cost of generating per kilowatt-hour (kWh) from solar energy was lower than energy generation from natural gas sources because of improvements in technology and the adoption of open bidding for power projects.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2019/09/04/open-bidding-bringing-down-cost-of-generating-renewable-energy|title=Open Bidding Brings Down Cost of Generating Renewable Energy|last=the star|date=4 September 2019|work=thestar|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref> The four lowest bids, which encompassed 365 MW out of 500 MW, came below the current cost of gas-fired power generation of 23.22 sen per kWh, with the lowest bid being 17.77 sen per kWh. This marks a 45% reduction from the lowest price of 32 sen per kWh for the second round of the Large Solar Project (LSS2) bid a few years ago.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/business/2019/09/518422/malaysia-needs-rm33b-investment-hit-renewable-energy-target-yeo|title=Malaysia needs RM33b investment to hit renewable energy target - Yeo|agency=Bernama|date=4 September 2019|work=nst|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nYeo is expecting that the upcoming 500MW plant would likely close below 24 sen per kWh, pending technical evaluation. Malaysia will see a more competitive and diversified power generation mix as technological advances in renewable energy and rising demand have made the access to the technology cheaper, contributing to a lower cost of electricity generation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.edgeprop.my/content/1582557/solar-electricity-cheaper-produce-yeo-says-lss3-bid-closes|title=Solar electricity cheaper to produce, Yeo says as LSS3 bid closes|last=Tan Xue Ying|date=3 September 2019|work=theedgemarkets|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nYeo also noted that Malaysia needed investments totalling RM33 billion in order to achieve its target of 20 percent electricity generation from renewable energy sources by 2025.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/malaysia-needs-rm33b-investment-to-hit-renewable-energy-target-yeo-HE1327180 |title=Malaysia needs RM33b investment to hit renewable energy target: Yeo |agency=[[Bernama]] |date=3 September 2019 |work=thesundaily}}</ref> Meantime, the Securities Commission has conducted a six-month study on green financing by forming a task force to provide a report on 21 action items for the facilitation of the RM33 billion investments into renewable energy. The Malaysian Government is committed to continue the current incentives for green investment for example Green Technology Financing Scheme, Green Investment Tax Allowance and Green Income Tax Exemption.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://themalaysianreserve.com/2019/09/04/latest-solar-farm-bids-lowest-at-17-8-sen/|title=Latest solar farm bids lowest at 17.8 sen |first1=Alifah |last1=Zainuddin |date=4 September 2019 |work=The Malaysian Reserve }}</ref>\n\n===The Second Biogas E-bidding Exercise and The First E-bidding for Small Hydro Power Systems===\nSustainable Energy Development Authority (SEDA) Malaysia is completing second biogas e-bidding exercise and inaugural e-bidding for small hydro power systems.\n\nIn a statement dated 23 July 2019, Yeo said the aim of the e-bidding process is to facilitate price discovery for renewable energy (RE) generated from biogas and small hydro resources, through healthy competition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/seda-midst-completing-ebidding-biogas-small-hydro-power|title=SEDA in midst of completing e-bidding for biogas, small hydro power|last=Chester Tay|date=23 July 2019|work=The Edge Markets|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nFeed-in Tariff (FiT) scheme had traditionally offered tariff at fixed rate. Having implemented the FiT for seven years, SEDA had improved price discovery of the tariff offered to renewable energy developer by way of competitive bidding. The inaugural e-bidding exercise for biogas was carried out in the fourth quarter of 2018. The schedule of e-bidding under the current phase includes 30MW and 160MW for biogas and small hydro respectively.\n\nAs at end of June 2019, SEDA approved 12,540 Feed-in Tariff (FiT) applications with a total capacity of 1,744.38 MW. This comprised 34.6 percent (small hydro), 25.4 percent (solar PV), 23.5 percent (biomass), 14.4 percent (biogas) and 2.1 percent (geothermal).\n\nMeanwhile, the total RE projects achieving commercial operation was 10,254 with total installed capacity of 621.96 MW (61.8 percent solar PV, 15.4 percent biomass, 11.5 percent biogas and 11.3 percent small hydro.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/business/2019/07/506652/seda-complete-second-biogas-e-bidding-exercise-and-small-hydro-power-systems|title=SEDA to complete second biogas e-bidding exercise and small hydro power systems|last=NST|date=23 July 2019|work=New Straits Times|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Energy Efficiency and Conservation Act (EECA)===\nA joint study by the Malaysian Government's Economic Planning Unit (EPU) and the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) estimated that Malaysia had potential energy savings of up RM46.92 billion from 2016 to 2030. The study shows that the main obstacle from widespread use of energy efficient practices is the lack of regulatory framework.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2018/11/01/minister-study-shows-energy-efficiency-could-unlock-rm47b-savings-over-15-y/1688894|title=Minister: Study shows energy efficiency could unlock RM47b savings over 15 years|last=Azril Annuar|date=1 November 2018|work=Malay Mail|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref> Therefore, MESTECC is working on the framework for the Energy Efficiency and Conservation Act (EECA), the act is expected to be tabled in the Dewan Rakyat at the end of 2019.<ref name=\"Bernama\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/07/04/energy-efficiency-and-conservation-bill-to-be-tabled-end-of-this-year-minis/1768303|title=Energy Efficiency and Conservation Bill to be tabled end of this year, says minister|agency=Bernama|date=4 July 2019|work=Malay Mail|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Energy Performance Contract (EPC)===\nApart from drafting the Energy Efficiency and Conservation Act, MESTECC has also reviewed and improved the National Energy Efficiency Action Plan (NEEAP) 2016-2025 and has set a new target to achieve at least 8 percent saving through energy efficiency by 2025.<ref name=\"Bernama\"/>\nMESTECC will focus on energy efficiency in the building sector as it has been identified internationally as one of the most cost-effective sectors to reduce energy consumption. \n\nBuilding electricity consumption comprises more than 50 percent of the electricity consumption in Malaysia.This shows that there is a great potential for cost savings if Malaysia can improve energy efficiency in buildings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://themalaysianreserve.com/2018/11/02/energy-efficiency-to-save-govt-nearly-rm47b-by-2030/|title=Energy efficiency to save govt nearly RM47b by 2030|last= P PREM KUMAR & ALIFAH ZAINUDDIN |date=2 November 2019|work=The Malaysian Reserve|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Decision on Accumulated Radioactive Residue at Lynas Advanced Materials Plant in Gebeng, Kuantan===\nFollowing the Executive Review Committee on Operations of [[Lynas#Lynas Advanced Materials Plant|Lynas Advance Material Plants]] (LAMP) in Gebeng which was presented to the MESTECC as scheduled on 27 November 2018, the Ministry is concerned with the increasing risk arising from the continued accumulation of residue without a viable solution to manage its accumulation in the near-term.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/local/mestecc-disallows-unlimited-accumulation-of-residual-waste-at-lynas-plant-GB210190|title=MESTECC disallows unlimited accumulation of residual waste at Lynas plant|agency=Bernama|date=4 December 2018|work=The Sun Daily|access-date=}}</ref> For this reason, the Ministry will not allow the unlimited accumulation of residue at LAMP.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/12/04/lynas-review-recommends-permanent-disposal-facility/|title=Lynas review recommends permanent disposal facility, Ministry says residue must be removed from Malaysia|last=Ong Han Sean|date=4 December 2018|work=The Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn this regard, the following pre-conditions will be applied to Lynas Malaysia for future licences/permission renewals:\n# The accumulated WLP residue, which contains radioactive materials, must be removed from Malaysia. (Note: the existing temporary storage licence expires on 2 September 2019.) The Ministry notes that Lynas Corporation Ltd., Australia (Lynas Australia) and Lynas Malaysia Sdn. Bhd. (Lynas Malaysia) had each presented letters of undertaking dated 23 February 2012 and 6 March 2012 respectively indicating their commitment to remove LAMP residue from Malaysia, if necessary.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/ministry-lynas-must-remove-radioactive-residue-malaysia|title=Ministry: Lynas must remove radioactive residue from Malaysia|last=Supriya Surendran|date=5 December 2018|work=The Edge Markets|access-date=}}</ref> \n# For the non-radioactive NUF scheduled waste, LAMP shall submit an action plan on the disposal of its accumulated wastes before it will be considered for future applications under Rule 9 (6) and 9 (7) of the Environmental Quality Regulations (Scheduled Waste) 2005. (Note: the current approval for the storage of scheduled wastes is valid until 15 February 2019).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/s/1699974/no-unlimited-storage-of-waste-for-lynas-says-ministry|title=No unlimited storage of waste for Lynas, says ministry|last= Emmanuel Santa Maria Chin|date=4 December 2018|work=Malay Mail|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Ministry is confident that this decision will help further ensure the well-being of the community and the environment.\n\n==Selangor State Assembly Representative for Damansara Utama (June 2013 - April 2018)==\n[[File:Yeo Bee Yin, 2013 (cropped).jpg|left|thumb|Yeo Bee Yin, in GE13]]\nIn the [[2013 Malaysian general election|2013 general election]] (GE13), Yeo contested for the first time and won the [[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]] constituency for Damansara Utama on a DAP ticket with 83.6% of the votes and a 30,689 majority, the highest majority for state seats in Malaysia. She was the youngest member of the  [[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]] then.<ref name=\"Blog\"/> Following her election, Yeo said that her main priorities were decreasing the high crime rates, traffic jams, as well as combating flash floods and poverty issues.<ref>{{cite news|last=Prasena|first=Priscilla|title=New rep vows openness|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2013/05/22/new-rep-vows-openness/|accessdate=25 May 2013|newspaper=[[Free Malaysia Today]]|date=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Rosmah and PERMATA ===\nIn March 2017, Yeo questioned the finances of the [[PERMATApintar National Gifted Center|PERMATApintar]] (commonly known just as PERMATA) programme, a child education and welfare programme, of which Prime Minister [[Najib Razak]]'s wife, [[Rosmah Mansor]] is the patron, urging for the transparency of the organisation's financial accounts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/357632|title=Rakyat has right to full picture of Permata, presses Yeo|date=2016-10-02|work=Malaysiakini|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref>\n\nYeo also questioned the need for a separate agency under the Prime Minister's Department with Rosmah, an individual not elected by the people, to have such a significant role in government, saying that early childhood development programmes such as PERMATA should be under the respective full ministries which are more equipped and have the personnel with more experience in the field.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/03/15/let-relevant-ministry-take-over-permata-dap-tells-rosmah/|title=Let relevant ministry take over Permata, DAP tells Rosmah|date=2017-03-15|work=Free Malaysia Today|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017 SMUE misappropriation allegation ===\nIn March 2017, Jamal Mohd Yunos, the [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO) Sungai Besar division chief had alleged that funds from the Selangor state government for the Skim Mesra Usia Emas (SMUE) had been misappropriated by Yeo. Yeo disproved the allegation with documents showing each SMUE payment made.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/03/22/dap-rep-refutes-funds-misuse-allegation-by-jamal-yunos/|title=DAP rep refutes funds misuse allegation by Jamal Yunos|date=2017-03-22|work=Free Malaysia Today|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref> Yeo appeared at the [[Malaysian Anti-Corruption Commission]] (MACC) office where Jamal was expected to show up to lodge a report. Yeo brought along a mirror with the words \"Nothing to Hide\" written on it to be presented to Jamal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/03/24/mirror-mirror-on-jamals-wall/|title=Mirror, mirror on Jamal's wall|date=2017-03-24|work=Free Malaysia Today|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref> Jamal however did not appear to lodge his report and the mirror was instead handed to his representative. Subsequently, Yeo filed a RM5 million suit against Jamal for defamation, in which, Jamal failed to appear at the High Court case management.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/07/13/jamal-yunos-no-show-in-court-for-libel-suit-by-yeo/|title=Jamal Yunos no-show in court for libel suit by Yeo|date=2017-07-13|work=Free Malaysia Today|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref>\n\n=== MCA Kampung Cempaka, Petaling Jaya land dispute ===\nIn September 2017, DAP lawmakers questioned the [[Malaysian Chinese Association]] (MCA) of Selangor about a one-acre plot of land in Kampung Cempaka, Petaling Jaya which was allegedly purchased under market price.\n\nMCA had applied for the land in 2006 and got approval from the state government in 2007 (which was then under Barisan Nasional). MCA then bought the land at RM 52,000 in 2008 at RM 1 per square foot (psf), when the land in fact was worth more than RM400psf. Yeo later on discovered the MCA's plans to convert the land to commercial status earlier in the year. She questioned the methods of how MCA managed to purchase the land under market price.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themalaysianinsight.com/s/14648/|title=DAP wants MCA to explain Petaling Jaya land buy {{!}} The Malaysian Insight|website=www.themalaysianinsight.com|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref> When the former [[Petaling Jaya Utara (federal constituency)|Petaling Jaya Utara]] MP, [[Chew Mei Fun]] of MCA was contacted on the matter, she denied being involved in the land application and declined to explain further.\n\nAfter the case was exposed to public knowledge, three MCA leaders - MCA Selangor Vice Chairperson Tang Song Chang, Chew and current MCA PJU division chief Tan Gim Tuan came forward to justify that the 1acre plot of land bought under market price will be used for public service. Yeo refuted this claim, explaining that if the land was actually for public service, then there would be no need for MCA to own the land as public service lands should be owned by the state government. Yeo also requested for proof or guarantee that MCA intended the land to be used for public service, and also further questioned the reason MCA applied for the land to be rezoned and converted from a \"water body\" to \"commercial land\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2017/09/29/yeo-to-mca-pj-land-to-be-used-for-public-services-really/|title=Yeo to MCA: PJ land to be used for public services \u2013 really?|date=2017-09-29|work=Free Malaysia Today|access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref>\n\nChew later threatened to sue Yeo and/or the DAP Member of Parliament for Petaling Jaya Utara then, [[Tony Pua]], to which the DAP leaders openly welcomed, holding on to their standing that they had not done anything defamatory towards Chew or the MCA by revealing truthful facts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/395678|title=Feel free to sue us, DAP reps tell MCA veep|date=2017-09-19|work=Malaysiakini|access-date=2018-03-07}}</ref>\n\n===Charity works===\nYeo's office runs two tuition centres in Damansara Bistari and Kampung Chempaka, which offer free classes for students between the ages of 7 to 17 from low-income families.<ref>{{Citation|last=ZAP Film|title=Pusat Tuisyen Rakyat Selangor|date=2016-07-18|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O834h1grhms|accessdate=2018-03-06}}</ref> She also runs a monthly [[food bank]] program providing basic necessities assistance to more than 100 people.\n\nShe also works with DAP's Impian Malaysia movement, being one of the pioneers of the first Impian Sarawak project in Kampung Sait, [[Sarawak]] which works to provide basic infrastructure such as roads, water, and electricity in Sarawak.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2016/03/15/real-change-means-working-on-the-impossible/|title=Real change means working on the impossible|author=Mikha Chan|publisher=[[Free Malaysia Today]]|date=15 March 2016|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe is the founder of LEAP (Leadership, Education, Activism and Politics), which aims to educate students on the political process and activism in Malaysia, such as the formation of political parties, [[election campaign]]s, constituency management, media relations, coalition formation and debates.<ref name=\"academic\"/>\n\nShe is also the founder of the Lawatan Anak Muda (LAM) Programme which allows young participants to visit the Malaysian Parliament and the Selangor State Assembly. Participants get the chance to have a Q&A session with a few Members of Parliament and state assemblypersons.<ref>{{Cite news\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | title = Yeo Bee Yin's Lawatan Anak Muda (LAM) Programme\n  | publisher = Yeo Bee Yin\uff08\u6768\u7f8e\u76c8\uff09Facebook\n  | language = ms\n  | date = 8 November 2017 \n  | url = https://business.facebook.com/yeobeeyin/posts/938841036269822?comment_id=938988902921702&comment_tracking=%7B%22tn%22%3A%22R0%22%7D\n  | accessdate = 23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n<ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=4 February 2017 }} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+'''[[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]''': N36 [[Damansara Utama (state constituency)|Damansara Utama]]<ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{cite web\n  | title = Malaysia General Election \n  | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data\n  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]\n  | url = http://undi.info/#\n  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://resultpru13.spr.gov.my/module/keputusan/paparan/paparan_laporan.php|title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM 13|work=Sistem Pengurusan Maklumat Pilihan Raya Umum|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n!|Year\n! colspan=\"2\" |Government\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n! colspan=\"2\" |Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{Party shading/Democratic Action Party}} |\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{nowrap|'''Yeo Bee Yin'''}} ([[Democratic Action Party|'''DAP''']])\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:right;\" |'''37,303'''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |'''84.21%'''\n| {{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Lim Choon Kin ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |6,614\n|14.93%\n| rowspan=\"2\" |44,654\n| rowspan=\"2\" |30,689\n| rowspan=\"2\" |83.63%\n|-\n| {{Party shading/Independent}} |\n| Liew Wei Beng ([[Independent politician|IND]])\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 380\n| 0.86%\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+'''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]''': P145 [[Bakri (federal constituency)|Bakri]], Johor.<ref name=\"undiinfo\"/><ref name=\"GE14 results\">{{cite web|url=https://keputusan.spr.gov.my/|title=SEMAKAN KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM KE - 14|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay|accessdate=17 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"The Star GE14\">{{cite web|url=https://election.thestar.com.my/|title=The Star Online GE14|work=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|accessdate=24 May 2018}} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref>\n!|Year\n!colspan=2|Government \n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{nowrap|'''Yeo Bee Yin'''